<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UCLA Dominates Gymnastics Meet  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- UCLA coach Valorie Kondos said earlier this
week the Bruins had the talent to dominate the NCAA women's
gymnastics meet. All they needed was to hit their routines.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't boasting. Her prediction was right on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins scored 197.3 points Friday night, turning in strong
team efforts on the floor, the vault and the beam to win their
second national title in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Utah surged late in the meet on the vault to place second at
196.875, almost half a point behind the Bruins. Georgia was third
at 196.8, followed by Nebraska (196.725) and Alabama (196.5).
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, which came into the meet expecting to challenge UCLA
for the title, had two early beam falls and never recovered,
placing sixth at 195.725.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins never fell at any station and locked up the title
before they started their final event, the beam. Lena Degteva got a
9.850 and Mohini Bhardwaj followed with a 9.875 on the beam to
complete the victory.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA started on the floor, its most consistent event all season,
and set the tone right away. Malia Jones and Kristin Parker opened
with 9.85s and Bhardwaj and Heidi Moneymaker each added 9.9s.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins then moved to the vault, where Parker, Degteva,
Bhardwaj and Moneymaker all delivered 9.9s. UCLA was steady on the
bars, with Bhardwaj leading the way with a 9.95 and Moneymaker
adding a 9.85.
</P>
<P>
   While Degteva and Moneymaker, both seniors, and Bhardwaj, a
junior, led the way, Kondos credited freshmen Jones, Parker, Doni
Thompson and Amy Young for the second straight night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody performed like I expected, and the freshmen carried
us for the second night in a row,'' Kondos said. ''That's a lot to
ask for kids that young.''
</P>
<P>
   A strong UCLA roster included four gymnasts -- Bhardwaj,
Thompson, Young and Onnie Willis -- with ties to the U.S. national
team. Degteva was a Canadian team alternate at the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Utah capped an injury-plagued season, surging to second place
with its final event, the vault. Ashley Keever started with a 9.7,
but it turned out that mark would be the one the Utes dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Allan and Theresa Wolf hit 9.9s, Angelika Schatton scored a
9.85, Denise Jones added another 9.9 and Deidra Graham finished
with a 9.85. It made up for several earlier injuries, including one
that ended the season for defending NCAA all-around champion
Theresa Kulikowski.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the best vaulting set we've had all year,'' Utah coach
Greg Marsden said. ''We knew we could do the other events well, but
in the vault we really sucked it up and had the meet of our life.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Kristi Lichey had a meet highlight, hitting a 10 on
the vault that attracted applause from fans on every side of the
Boise State Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   NCAA championships site: http://www.ncaachampionships.com
</P>
<P>
   Boise State athletics site: http://www.broncosports.com
</P>
</TEXT>
