<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Dives 617; Nasdaq Plunges 355
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market collapsed Friday as the Dow Jones
industrials and Nasdaq composite index both suffered record one-day point drops.
The Dow dropped 617.78 points, or 5.7 percent, to 10,305.77. On the NYSE, losers
led gainers 2,672-434. The Nasdaq dropped 355.49, or almost 10 percent, to
3,321.29. The Dow and Nasdaq set one-day percentage decline records. This week,
the Nasdaq fell 25.3 percent, while the Dow slid 7.3 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Relatives Respond in Elian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's Miami relatives said Friday that the boy would
be psychologically harmed if he were turned over immediately to his father.
Relatives said they were willing to bring Elian to a meeting with his father,
but only within close driving distance of Miami so as not to traumatize him. The
U.S. government had asked a federal appeals panel to order Elian's great-uncle
to turn the 6-year-old Cuban refugee over to his father. The Justice Department
said Lazaro Gonzalez should receive no help from a court until he surrenders the
boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Lawmakers OK START II
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- As Russian lawmakers approved the START II treaty to scrap
thousands of U.S. and Russian nuclear warheads, the government warned it would
abandon all arms-control pacts if Washington goes ahead with an anti-missile
system. The swift approval of START II was President Vladimir Putin's first
major foreign policy action and underlined his strong authority and the
willingness of the new centrist majority in parliament to work with the
government. Putin warned that Moscow would pull out of arms agreements if the
United States breaches the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Hits GOP on Education, Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- President Clinton accused Republicans Friday of shortchanging
schools to pay for huge tax cuts and said Americans should look at the GOP's
budget and ask, ''How does all this add up?'' ''I think it's wrong to spend
about $100 of the surplus on tax cuts for every $1 you spend on education,''
Clinton told reporters, university spokesmen and others at a gathering of the
Education Writers Association. The House and Senate approved a $1.83 trillion
package yesterday that includes big tax cuts as well as reductions in many
domestic programs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tentative U.S. Trade Deal Reached
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders welcomed a tentative agreement on
legislation extending new trade benefits to African, Central American and
Caribbean nations Friday and suggested final action could come next month. A
monthslong logjam on the bill, a top Clinton administration trade initiative,
was broken last night as leaders from the House and the Senate met to hammer out
a compromise. Although some staff work remained, leaders characterized the
agreement as a major breakthrough.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Court To Address Death Appeals
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The Florida Supreme Court Friday voided most of a
new law intended to speed death penalty appeals but promised to address the
issue itself. The justices unanimously found that parts of the Death Penalty
Reform Act of 2000, which was passed during a special legislative session in
January, violate the separation of powers clause in the Florida Constitution.
Only the judicial branch of government has the power to make court rules, the
justices concluded.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Breaks $80 Million Mark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has broken the $80 million mark in his
Republican presidential campaign, adding to his own fund-raising record while
replenishing his war chest after an expensive primary effort. The campaign
raised around $7.6 million between March 1 and April 6, spokesman Scott
McClellan said Friday, three-quarters of the goal of $10 million by the end of
April. Bush's total for the campaign is now more than $81 million.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Bungled Nurse Still Working
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A nurse bungled the care of at least six patients --
including two who died -- but is still working at a Veterans Affairs hospital in
Phoenix, according to a VA report that was sent to the White House and Congress
this week. VA investigators said nurse anesthetist David T. Polner removed
breathing tubes too early and made other errors in the care of the six patients
between 1993 and 1999. The VA concluded that Polner's actions did not kill the
two patients who died, although reviewers cited problems with incomplete records
in both cases and said no other cause could be found for one man's death.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Beat Pirates 8-5 in 12 Innings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mike Piazza homered twice in his first career five-hit
game and Melvin Mora had a go-ahead, two-run single in the 12th inning as the
New York Mets beat the Pittsburgh Pirates 8-5 Friday. The Mets outhit the
Pirates 20-11, but didn't win it until Mora followed Rey Ordonez's single and
Benny Agbayani's bad-hop double with a bloop single to center off Jose Silva
(2-1).
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
