<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albany Med does first heart transplant in northeastern New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Albany Medical Center's first heart
transplant patient remained in critical condition late Friday night
with doctors saying they had high hopes his new heart will take
hold.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-member surgical team performed the five-hour operation on
56-year-old William Van Benschoten of the Dutchess County town of
Pleasant Valley Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new heart is very vigorous and 100 times better than the
old one,'' said Dr. Charles Canver, head of the surgical team and
director of the Heart Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ''The technical aspects of the operation went very smoothly and
the heart has good pressure, good rhythm and is working very
well,'' Canver said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Benschoten, one of five patients on the medical center's
heart transplant waiting list, was admitted to the hospital on
April 4. The donated heart came from a 28-year-old unidentified man
in northern New York, who had suffered a fatal stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Van Benschoten's family members publicly thanked the donor's
family at a news conference held at the hospital Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's ready to live the rest of his life,'' daughter Rebecca
Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany Medical Center Heart Institute received state Health
Department approval to perform heart transplants last May, after
starting the application process in June 1998. Hospital officials
said they hope to perform a dozen transplants by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Strong Memorial Hospital in Rochester received state approval at
the same time but has not performed a transplant yet.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the closest transplant centers for patients from
northeastern New York were in New York City and Boston. Buffalo
General Hospital also had a heart transplant center, but it
discontinued its program in January. Albany Medical Center will now
serve patients in 25 counties in New York and Western New England.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's transplantation procedure got under way around 10 p.m.
Wednesday when a potential donor was identified. Albany Medical
Center's transplant coordinators assisted the family of the donor
after the decision to donate organs was made.
</P>
<P>
   Canver and Dr. Mike Hill, an Albany surgical resident, traveled
to the donor hospital before dawn Friday, removed the heart, and
returned to Albany by 5 a.m. The transplantation started at 5:50
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Canver performed approximately 200 heart transplants before
coming to Albany Medical Center in late 1998. He was previously
director of the heart transplant program at the University of
Wisconsin Hospital and Clinics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
