<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly speaker, City Council speaker bicker over budget  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The two most powerful ''speakers'' in New
York government -- state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and New
York City Council Speaker Peter Vallone -- are bickering over how
fairly the city is being treated in the new state budget.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats, often allied on fiscal and policy questions,
are at odds over how the $78 billion spending plan which state
legislators expect to pass next week will affect the city.
</P>
<P>
   A letter Vallone sent Assembly members from New York City and
other lawmakers expressed ''great dismay'' at budget provisions
''which will threaten the city's fiscal health in future years.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver, rebutting this, accused the speaker Friday of
disparaging the work of New York City Democrats in the Assembly
''for your own personal benefit.'' A Silver aide said that referred
to what Silver sees as Vallone's sometimes-too-close relationship
with Republican New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone is eyeing a possible run for mayor in 2001 when
Giuliani's current term ends. Giuliani is running for the U.S.
Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton this year. Because of the
city's term limits, he cannot seek a third term as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Vallone objected to a decision by legislative
leaders and Gov. George Pataki to maintain New York City's
revenue-sharing aid at $328 million, while raising it by 5 percent
for localities outside the city. Vallone said that deprives the
city of almost $28 million in the next state fiscal year, and $16.5
million annually in years after that.
</P>
<P>
   ''But more than the loss in revenues, the exclusion of New York
City from consideration for additional revenue-sharing funds sets a
dangerous precedent,'' Vallone said. ''The New York City Council
cannot stay silent while our fundamental eligibility for increased
revenue-sharing funds is ceded to others.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Silver was blasting Vallone Friday, the city
council speaker was holding a City Hall news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''Albany is executing another squeeze play on New York City,''
Vallone complained in a reference to last year's decision by the
Legislature and governor to rescind the city's income tax on
commuters; a decision made without city officials' assent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to revenue-sharing aid to municipalities, Vallone
also said the city will lose out when the state reinstitutes
revenue-sharing aid to counties -- but not New York City -- in the
next budget to help them pay for a new health care program for the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Silver shot back that New York City already gets more than its
share of aid under the revenue-sharing program, which the Assembly
speaker said ''was intended to be primarily population-based.'' New
York City has 41 percent of the state's population, but receives
more than 57 percent of revenue-sharing aid, Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver also took issue with Vallone's contention that the city's
eligibility for revenue is being ''ceded'' to other municipalities.
While New York City enjoys a $2 billion-plus surplus, Silver said,
several upstate cities are facing deficits and are in ''desperate
need of cash assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Several upstate cities have not only not reaped the benefits
of the current economic boom but in fact face substantial budget
deficits, which are likely to be recurring in nature,'' Silver
said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's biggest cities outside of New York City will get
special infusions of aid in the new state budget: Buffalo ($22
million-plus), Rochester ($15 million), Yonkers ($15 million),
Syracuse ($10 million) and Albany ($4.5 million). Buffalo, in fact,
makes out especially well since its money comes besides a
previously announced grant of $50 million for Adelphia
Communications to build a new office tower, and $25 million to
forgive an existing state loan given to construct HSBC Arena, home
of the Buffalo Sabres. Adelphia inherited the debt when it
purchased the team.
</P>
<P>
   Silver also outlined a series of bills, many passed recently at
New York City's request, which have saved the city substantial
sums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
