<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maryland company building New York's first commercial wind powerstation  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, N.Y. (AP) -- Calling wind energy the ''future of
America,'' U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson headed a
groundbreaking for New York state's first commercial wind energy
station on a hilltop in Madison County.
</P>
<P>
   The seven turbine, 11.5-megawatt Madison Wind Project will the
be the largest wind-powered generating facility in the eastern
United States when it begins operation in September, 45 miles
southeast of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest message that we should have gotten from the OPEC
issue and the high price of gasoline is that we have got to
concentrate on renewable energy. Like wind. Like solar. Like
biomass. This is really the future,'' the secretary told a crowd of
200.
</P>
<P>
   The wind station is being built by Bethesda, Md.-based PG&AMP;E, one
of the nation's largest independent power producers with nearly $21
billion in revenues and operations in 27 states.
</P>
<P>
   ''That one of the leading energy companies in the country is
taking this kind of initiative is a strong sign of wind power's
feasibility,'' Richardson told reporters after the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Using the most advanced technology, each 220-foot-tall,
three-bladed windmill generates up to 1.65 megawatts of power.
Collectively, the Madison wind station would provide enough
electricity to supply about 5,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   However, PG&AMP;E wants to sell its wind power to commercial or
industrial companies, to energy marketing companies, or to
utilities. It does not expect to sell directly to residential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most U.S. wind plants have been built under contract to
supply utilities obligated to buy the power rather than in the
competitive wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E Chairman Robert D. Glynn Jr. noted that energy generated by
windmills reduces the need for fossil fuel-burning, which pumps
pollutants into the air.
</P>
<P>
   In an average wind year, the Madison station will spare the
environment up to 12,000 tons of carbon dioxide, 65 tons of sulfur
dioxide and 19 tons of nitrogen oxides, Glynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Wind power also presents itself as a ''21st-century cash crop''
for farmers, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Madison wind turbines occupy fields leased from dairy
farmers Carl and Jim Stone and their neighbors, Harley and Brenda
Mason. The farmers will be able to plant corn and alfalfa around
the turbines next year. Lease payments will help pay the farms'
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if you've heard or not, but dairy farming is not
real good,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Several wind resource facilities are being planned elsewhere in
the state, including one just a few miles down the road in Fenner.
There, Atlantic Renewable Energy Corp. of Washington, D.C., is
planning to build a 10- to 15-megawatt wind farm. Atlantic helped
develop the Madison project before selling its interest to PG&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic also has a plan in the works for a 100-megawatt wind
farm in Lewis County where Niagara Mohawk conducted a pilot project
with a .7 megawatt station from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Vestas-American Wind Technology Inc. has plans to develop a
Wyoming County wind farm with a capacity between 4.6 and 9.2
megawatts. The New York State Energy Research and Development
Authority also has a wind farm planned and is presently negotiating
financing for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The United States now has a more than 2,500 megawatts of wind
power generating capacity, about one-fifth of the world's total,
according to the American Wind Energy Association. Much of the U.S.
capacity is located in California and the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the energy department's goal is to double that
capacity by 2005 and double it again by 2010. Wind power can
eventually provide as much as 20 percent of the nation's energy
needs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It already is the world's fastest-growing energy source,
increasing from 25 percent to 30 percent yearly. More than $4
billion was invested into wind power projects worldwide last year,
the AWEA said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's winds are modest compared with those that blow across
the Great Plains. But they are still considerable, according to
industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   The American Wind Energy Association ranks New York 14th
nationally in wind resources with a capacity of up to
23,000-megawatts. Most of the best sites are in central and western
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the PG&AMP;E wind station may depend on which way the
economic winds blow.
</P>
<P>
   Wind power is still relatively costly compared with conventional
power sources. It's sold mainly to customers who want to promote
the use of a nonpolluting, renewable source.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of wind power has dropped dramatically in recent
years -- from 50 cents a kilowatt-hour in 1980 to a current range of
3 to 6 cents a kilowatt-hour, according to the U.S. Department of
Energy.
</P>
<P>
   The current wholesale price of conventional power is about 2.5
cents to 3 cents a kilowatt-hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
