<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-serving assemblywoman won't seek re-election  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- After more than a quarter century in office,
Assemblywoman Elizabeth Connelly says she will step down when her
term expires in December to spend more time with her family.
</P>
<P>
   The longest-serving woman in the history of the New York state
Legislature said Friday she will not seek re-election this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just felt that after 27 years that it was time,'' Connelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old Democrat cited the long, tiring commute between
her Staten Island district and Albany as well as the
unpredictability of the Legislature schedule as other factors
leading to her decision. She also said she's been so busy that she
could not get to her physical therapist to address the back pain
she has suffered since Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But Connelly said leaving her Assembly seat doesn't necessarily
mean political retirement. She said county Democrats have courted
her as a possible candidate for borough president, a position
currently held by Republican Guy Molinari.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm leaving the door open,'' she said. ''I would never rule
anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly currently serves as speaker pro tempore, usually
presiding from the podium in the sometimes raucous 150-member
house. As temporary speaker -- the real speaker, Sheldon Silver,
rarely presides -- she recognizes speakers during debates and makes
decisions on parliamentary questions, all the while pleading for
quiet and order in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The position is also the highest-ranking leadership post ever
held by a woman in Assembly history.
</P>
<P>
   She was a homemaker in 1973 when she was asked by Democratic
Party leaders to run in a special election. She won, becoming
Staten Island's first female elected official. She won her
subsequent re-election bids for the Assembly seat representing a
heavily Democratic district.
</P>
<P>
   In the Assembly, Connelly had served as chairwoman of her
chamber's committee on mental health and hygiene, which in the past
also covered alcohol and substance abuse. She has also been a
strong supporter of antigambling initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Assemblyman Eric Vitaliano, also of Staten Island,
called Connelly's work on those issues her ''greatest legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Albany scene today, when those interests come up, the
first name that jumps to anybody's tongue is Betty Connelly,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vitaliano said he was ''stunned'' by Connelly's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm deeply saddened that I'm losing my mentor but thrilled
that she and (her husband) Bob can do what they want to do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Sen. John Marchi, a Staten Island Republican, ''I will
miss them both, but I am pleased to know they leave in good health
for other important and interesting activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Connelly will be ''sorely missed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''New York state is better off by having Betty Connelly giving
us ... a little over a quarter century of serving here,'' Silver
said. ''She's earned everyone's respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly said there are a number of young people in her party
who would be qualified to replace her but she declined to give any
names.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks attractive when you're not running against an
incumbent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Lavelle, chairman of the Staten Island Democratic Party,
agreed that it is too early to determine Connelly's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   During her first year in office, Connelly was one of only four
women in the Assembly. Today, there are 36 women in that chamber, a
number that is ''still not a heck of a lot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've come a long way, but I don't think we've progressed as
far as we've wanted,'' Connelly said. ''I think we could do more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
