<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suns 112, Clippers 88  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- With three forwards scoring in double figures,
the Phoenix Suns edged closer to clinching homecourt advantage in
the first round of the playoffs Friday night by handing the Los
Angeles Clippers their 15th consecutive defeat, 112-88.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have won four in a row, two of them against the
Clippers, and have a two-game lead over San Antonio with three to
play in the race for the No. 4 spot in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Rogers scored 22, Shawn Marion 20 and Cliff Robinson 17
for the Suns, who outscored the Clippers by an average of 104-81 in
their four-game sweep this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Nesby scored 21 for Los Angeles, but only two in the
second half. Michael Olowokandi had 15 points and 12 rebounds for
the Clippers. Lamar Odom scored 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had sputtered in their previous two victories over the
Clippers and Vancouver. This one was easier, although the Suns
didn't turn it into a blowout until well into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix never trailed and led 52-40 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns shot out to a 16-5 lead. The Clippers, who have lost to
Phoenix 10 consecutive times, cut it to 24-23 with an 11-2 run,
then the Suns reeled off 10 in a row to go up 34-23 on Oliver
Miller's stuff with 10:13 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's three-point play put the Suns ahead 66-50 with 6:38
left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson scored 13, Marion 12 and Rogers 10 in the first half.
Nesby scored 19 in the first half, 14 in the first quarter. But the
rest of the Clippers were ice cold. Los Angeles shot 28 percent
(11-for-39) in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Suns' Kevin Johnson missed his second consecutive game
with a groin strain. He may return for Sunday's game against Utah.
... The Clippers were without Maurice Taylor (sore left ankle) and
Derek Anderson (lower back spasms). ... Miller had seven points in
his first appearance in three games and first significant playing
time in six games. ... If Utah wins at San Antonio on Saturday, the
Suns can clinch the first-round homecourt advantage by beating the
Jazz on Sunday. ... Phoenix has the third-best home record in the
NBA at 32-7. ... The Clippers have the league's worst road record,
4-36.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
