<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Charges in LA's Belmont Scandal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- No criminal charges will be filed over the
multimillion-dollar construction of the Belmont Learning Center on
a polluted site, top prosecutors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the school district's auditor on the $170 million
fiasco ''simply does not support the allegations of criminal
wrongdoing,'' Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   California Attorney General Bill Lockyer and City Attorney James
Hahn also informed auditor Don Mullinax that they did not find any
evidence that state agencies or others committed environmental
crimes or failed to perform legally required duties.
</P>
<P>
   ''No misdemeanor violations have been proved,'' said the report
by Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   An after-hours call seeking comment from the Los Angeles Unified
School District was not immediately returned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The unfinished center is the nation's costliest high school
project. Work was halted in 1998 after explosive methane gas and
toxic hydrogen sulfide were found on the former oil field near
downtown. In January, the Board of Education voted to abandon the
project as a high school, although the debate on what to do with it
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax sent his report on the Belmont scandal to the U.S.
attorney's office and the city, county and state prosecutors last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax has said former school board members and senior staff
were so lax in their management of the project that they should be
sued. He also found that subcontractors overbilled the district,
and said criminal charges could be warranted against the main
developer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0113 </TRAILER>
