<HEADLINE> Dozens Cited in L.A. Janitors March  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Four state Assembly members were among dozens
of people cited Friday for blocking an intersection during a
massive march by striking janitors.
</P>
<P>
   Police issued 35 citations for failure to disperse after some of
the estimated crowd of 2,000 janitors and supporters sat down at
Wilshire and Westwood boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   The sit-down was planned by the Service Employees International
Union Local 1877 to increase pressure on cleaning contractors to
meet the union's wage demands, said Blanca Gallegos, a union
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the type of demonstration you're going to see until there
is some significant movement at the table,'' Gallegos said. ''The
janitors have been sacrificing now for 12 days and they want to go
back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the union and contractors met for eight hours
Thursday in the first talks since March 31. The talks resumed
Friday afternoon but ended after about six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos said the two sides remain far apart on wages.
</P>
</TEXT>
