<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tries To Dispel Superstition  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Olive-clad troops and schoolchildren in gym suits
came to the capital's military museum by the busload to see optical
illusions demystified and the magic of conception and birth
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which is now set to tour the country, is part of
an intense campaign by the government designed to encourage the
Chinese to embrace science and reject increasingly popular
superstitious beliefs -- and is the latest weapon in its bid to
stamp out the Falun Gong spiritual movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Health and longevity depend on science,'' says a display
devoted to describing medicine and surgery and condemning the
rejection of medicine in favor of spiritual cures.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ''Uphold Science and Civilization, Oppose
Superstition and Ignorance,'' features photos of mass suicides by
members of cults in other countries and testimonies from
heartbroken relatives of Falun Gong members said to have died or
committed gruesome murders.
</P>
<P>
   But the main focus is on selling science to the masses through
basic education and hands-on displays showing how those who claim
to have supernatural powers trick people to gain their trust.
</P>
<P>
   With the push of a button, a card with pictures of a birdcage on
one side and a bird on the other twirl, causing the bird to appear
as if it is sitting in the cage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our own vision causes this to happen. But it can be used to
cheat people,'' said a retired military officer, who would give
only his surname, Shao.
</P>
<P>
   Another display shows the division of cells in an embryo after
conception and the chromosomes that determine a child's sex.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are just cells. There is no such thing as reincarnation
of a spirit,'' the notation next to the exhibit says.
</P>
<P>
   A recent government survey found that beliefs in fortunetelling,
ghosts, witchcraft and supernatural abilities are spreading, the
official China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on Falun Gong began in earnest after 10,000 members
staged a silent vigil around the Communist Party leadership
compound last April.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the intensity and size of the group -- official
estimates once put its membership at 70 million -- leaders labeled
it a threat to communist rule and a public menace, banning it on
July 22 and declaring it a cult.
</P>
<P>
   But the faithful still meet in secret and stage protests,
risking beatings, arrest and imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   ''After such a long time, the shadowy ghost of Falun Gong has
not dispersed,'' the party newspaper Guangming Daily said recently.
''The rotting, stinking corpse is still a malign poison in our
midst.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, police arrested at least two van-loads of Falun
Gong adherents after they unfurled banners on Tiananmen Square, the
symbolic political heart of China.
</P>
<P>
   The government's inability to eradicate Falun Gong, despite a
nationwide campaign in which thousands have been arrested, mirrors
the failure of a wider decades-long battle by the Communist Party
to stamp out ''superstitious'' groups and wean Chinese of their
fondness for traditional mystical practices like fortunetelling and
ancestor worship.
</P>
<P>
   After 50 years of rule by the officially atheist Communist
Party, villagers still burn paper cards and houses for departed
spirits and stage ''weddings'' between corpses of dead sons and
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cults can cause great harm to society. We want to help people
know how to recognize a cult and withstand its temptations,'' said
Cui Jianping, deputy director of the Science Popularization
Department of the China Science Association, a sponsor of the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong members contend that their practices, which draw from
Buddhism, the quasi-martial art of qigong and the beliefs of
founder Li Hongzhi, a former government clerk, promote good health
and morality.
</P>
<P>
   The tug-of-war between science and superstition continues a long
tradition of suppressing doomsday cults and secret societies that
the emperors and later revolutionary leader Mao Tse-Tung viewed as
threats to stability.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent report by Amnesty International, in the 17
months before Falun Gong was banned, police reported they had
cracked 11,870 cases of ''using feudal superstition to disrupt
social order or defraud property'' and arrested 21,400 suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Police also have closed down hundreds of local sects and illegal
religious organizations, including evangelical Protestant and
Catholic churches operating outside state control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0123 </TRAILER>
