<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges 617; Nasdaq Sinks 355  </HEADLINE>
By NOELLE KNOX, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors have the weekend to lick their wounds
and rethink their trading strategy after one of Wall Street's worst
weeks ever ended in a selling stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks lost almost $2 trillion in value this week, with the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index falling an unprecedented 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's killing me. It's been a bad week,'' said Joe Ayala, a
lawyer in Sacramento, Calif. But he wasn't prepared to bail out
when markets resume trading Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got most of my stuff in retirement accounts, so I'm
hanging on for the long term -- I'm not going anywhere,'' Ayala
said.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke Friday as the Dow Jones industrial average plummeted a
record 617.78 points, or 5.7 percent, to close at 10,305.77. Its
weekly drop of more than 805 points also was a record.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq dropped a record 355.49 points, or 9.7 percent, to
3,321.29, falling deeper into bear-market territory. Since hitting
a record 5,048.62 on March 10, the Nasdaq has tumbled 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Already battered by days of heavy selling, the markets turned
ugly Friday after the government released a surprisingly bad
inflation report. As prices tumbled, many who bought stocks with
borrowed money were forced to sell to repay loans -- accelerating
the downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a semi-panic, almost a full cascading deterioration,''
said Ned Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street Global
Advisors. ''The real question is, have we reached the nadir of
emotion?''
</P>
<P>
   The rout was stunning. The Wilshire Associates Equity Index --
which represents the combined market value of all New York Stock
Exchange, American and Nasdaq issues -- ended the week at $12.5
trillion, down $1.9 trillion from the previous week. It still was
up from the $12.1 trillion of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow at one point was down an unprecedented 722 points.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff decimated several sectors, including computer
software and semiconductors, brokerage companies, banks and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger for the collapse was pulled in Washington, where the
Labor Department said consumer prices surged more than expected in
March, reflecting higher costs for everything from gasoline to
housing.
</P>
<P>
   The figures rekindled worries that the Federal Reserve not only
would raise interest rates again, but might be more aggressive in
trying to cool down the economy in order to remove the threat of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has already raised rates five times since June, each
time by a quarter-point in borrowing charges. Now, many investors
fear a half-point increase as early as May.
</P>
<P>
   Even that may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk is the U.S. economy does not slow enough and the Fed
has to raise rates in the second half of the year, in spite of the
election. That is not priced into the market,'' said Nick Sargen,
an investment strategist for J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates raise corporate costs and hurt profits.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop in
high-tech stocks is a growing sense that investors pushed those
issues too far last year, when the Nasdaq rose an unprecedented 86
percent. The frenzy for technology stocks gave many young, unproven
Internet companies market values they did not yet deserve, analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   The market volatility also has caused several companies to
postpone stock offerings and mergers and acquisitions. And that is
hurting investment banks and brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find any consensus on what might happen Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Next week could be extremely rough,'' said Gary Kaltbaum,
chief technical analyst at J.W. Genesis Securities in Boca Raton,
Fla. ''I'd like to believe that we've now had the panic selloff
that will allow the market to move higher. But every support that
we crashed through this week could become resistance going up.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the markets closed off their lows of the day,
which could be a positive sign.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP;
Sons, was among the hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ''Corrections are designed to work off excesses and create
opportunities,'' he said. ''I've been telling people to get their
wish list together. It's the best time to buy stocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0129 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few Panic After Wall Street Losses  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The carnage on Wall Street brought out the best
and worst in everybody. Those inclined to panic, sold. For others,
it was an opportunity to pounce.
</P>
<P>
   In New York's Times Square, a crowd gathered around the windows
of Nasdaq's electronic signboard Friday to see how bad the damage
was. Some gasped as they learned the Nasdaq index had slumped 34
percent from its high point five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   To Laurence Kaplan, who works in a clothing company nearby, the
solution was obvious. Shouting hurriedly into his cell phone, he
urged his colleague to ''Sell, sell, sell!''
</P>
<P>
   Others took the decline in stride. Cynthia Middleton, a business
development executive for AT&AMP;T, was also advising a friend on her
cell phone, but in far more measured tones.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't make sense to get out now,'' she said. ''You don't
experience a loss unless you sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people did sell Friday. When the dust finally settled
the Nasdaq composite index finished down a record 355.49 points, or
9.7 percent. The Dow was off 617.78 points, also a record drop.
</P>
<P>
   All the excitement Friday brought a bemused grin to the face of
Anatoliy Basov, a 32-year-old New Jersey resident. Basov, a
software engineer, was puffing nonchalantly on a cigarette as the
buzz grew.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm an investor, not a trader,'' Basov said. ''There's nothing
to worry about. The next time I plan to take money out of the
market is in 14 years when my kid goes to college. It's just time
for a regular adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Many investors across the nation displayed a measure of calm
among the craziness. For them, it was an opportunity to show
resolve and long-term thinking during trying times.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure I'm unsettled,'' said Dan Zwiren, a senior vice president
with an Internet telephony company in New York. ''It's going to
take time to repair this and rebuild investor confidence. But I'm
staying with what I have. I'm not happy about it, but I'm not
panicking either.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's weird that it keeps dropping like this. It's just
bizarre,'' says Dan Shore, 40, a publishing representative who
works in southern Minnesota. ''But I assume it will turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, however, the weeklong stock market disaster -- the
Nasdaq index is down 25 percent over the past five days -- has taken
its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Moskowitz grabbed his chest and took a step back as he
laid his eyes on the stock market ticker scrolling across the lobby
of Charles Schwab's lobby at the brokerage's San Francisco
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real blood bath,'' said Moskowitz, 58, of Mill
Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Moskowitz said he probably would troll the market for
bargains and add to his portfolio of about 35 stocks, which include
several tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there should be some good deals out there,'' he said.
''There was so much hot air in the market, that this is probably a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors have seen all they care to. David Hummel, a
23-year-old computer engineer for an online mortgage company in New
York, had been making about a dozen stock trades a day from his
work terminal. He's getting out for good.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't afford to lose anymore,'' said Hummel, fidgeting
nervously with his tongue stud. ''I guess this is what you get for
believing the ads from these online brokers making you think it's
all so easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CNN Settles Defamation Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- CNN has one less legal battle on its hands from
the network's ill-fated 1998 report that accused the military of
using nerve gas on Vietnam War-era defectors.
</P>
<P>
   CNN on Friday settled a lawsuit brought by retired U.S. Army
Gen. John Singlaub, who had been named as a source in the report.
Terms weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub was a former commander of the Studies and Operations
Group, an elite unit of the Army Special Forces accused of being
involved in the nerve gas operations. He had been named by a former
CNN producer as a source for the Operation Tailwind report.
</P>
<P>
   CNN retracted its June 7, 1998 report about a month after airing
it because it could not verify its accuracy. The network fired two
producers and a third resigned over the story. The lead reporter,
Peter Arnett, was reprimanded and ultimately left the network.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had an extensive, two-day mediation conference, during
which General Singlaub was able to air his grievances and
defendants were able to respond,'' said Keith Mitnik, Singlaub's
lawyer. ''The sessions were very productive and paved the way for a
resolution of the disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   A CNN spokeswoman had no comment, other than to confirm a
settlement had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub appeared on camera during the Operation Tailwind
report, explaining why it could be important to kill defectors. But
his lawsuit alleged that CNN's story made it appear he had been
involved in an effort to use sarin gas against Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The general was quoted more extensively in a CNN ''Impact''
broadcast that aired eight months prior to the Tailwind report. His
lawsuit said CNN defamed him by suggesting on ''Impact'' that
Singlaub might have been involved in an American bombing of
American soldiers in Laos to destroy evidence they were in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   Mitnik said that terms of the settlement were confidential,
''other than to say the financial portion of the settlement dealt
only with the 'Impact' broadcast in which General Singlaub was
featured, rather than Tailwind, in which he appeared only
briefly.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an important distinction for CNN and its lawyers, since
they could argue that Singlaub's settlement not be used as a
precedent in other Tailwind-related lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   CNN has been sued by other former military officials who served
in the Vietnam-era Special Forces, and those cases are still
pending.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also settles Singlaub's cases against Arnett, the
producers involved and Time magazine. Time, a corporate cousin of
CNN, wrote a story based on the Tailwind investigation and later
retracted it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub had been countersued for defamation by April Oliver,
one of the fired CNN producers who worked on the report. Oliver
said that Singlaub had ''confirmed the central ideas of the
Tailwind broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, Oliver's lawsuit against Singlaub has
been dropped, Mitnik said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0131 </TRAILER>
