<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Sopranos' Fans Have Long Wait  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Will Tony Soprano act on his fantasies about his
psychiatrist? Will the feds get him? Will his sister stay far away?
</P>
<P>
   Fans of HBO's ''The Sopranos'' will have to wait nearly a year
to see if those questions will be answered. After striking ratings
gold with its season finale this week, the show is going away for
an unusually long hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   The third, 13-episode season of ''The Sopranos'' won't start
until March 2001, to give series creator David Chase more time to
write. The second season began this past January.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process this year was very taxing on him,'' HBO chief
executive Jeff Bewkes said Friday. ''He was pressed a lot. He wants
time to think of the story arc about how the next two seasons
develop.''
</P>
<P>
   To fill the time for anxious fans, HBO will rerun the second
season of ''The Sopranos'' once this summer, and probably again
next winter as the third season approaches. The network may also
air episodes from the drama's first season.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the numbers, viewers caught up with the critics in
their fascination with New Jersey mob boss Soprano and his extended
family.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for the Sunday night episodes this year were 63 percent
higher than for the first year, according to HBO, leaving Bewkes
less worried about the 11-month hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will come back and it will be fine,'' he said. ''Look at
what happened this season -- it was the same thing. It had been away
for nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's episode, which featured the burial at sea of mob snitch
Salvatore ''Big Pussy'' Bompensiero, drew an audience of 9 million
people. One-quarter of the television homes that get HBO were tuned
in. About a quarter of the nation's TV homes get HBO.
</P>
<P>
   It was the highest rating for any original HBO show in the
network's history, and the biggest audience for anything on HBO
since last April's cable debut of ''Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase and his ensemble of actors are signed up for two more
years of ''The Sopranos,'' a total of 26 episodes.
</P>
<P>
   After that, if Chase says he's through, the series is over,
Bewkes said. HBO, because it is subscriber-based and doesn't take
advertising, is under less pressure to keep its franchises running
if they are past their peak, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the reasons that our shows work and cut through is
because we don't do it that way,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0133 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
