<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editors Examine Coverage of Youth  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- News outlets need to give reporters more time
to ask the questions that give youth and school stories more depth,
editors were told by critics of how the media cover young people.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has to be a crime, usually a serious crime, to get any
coverage,'' said Beth Frerking, director of the University of
Maryland's Casey Journalism Center for Children and Families.
''It's more than covering a school shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a meeting of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors, Frerking said news reporters either ignore stories about
youth and families or provide only superficial coverage when they
do write about child abuse, schools or foster care.
</P>
<P>
   A survey released at Friday's discussion suggests that editors
and reporters have much work to do to improve their ways.
</P>
<P>
   Responses showed that:
</P>
<P>
   --Three in five reporters and editors said there's too little
coverage of youth and family issues.
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy percent said they've covered school violence, compared
with 51 percent who say they've worked on stories about early
childhood development.
</P>
<P>
   --Eighty percent said journalists need special training to cover
youth and families.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released by the Foundation for American
Communications, is based on 420 randomly selected journalists
interviewed this winter. The margin of error is plus or minus 4.9
percentage points, said the Champaign, Ill.-based Research Survey
Service, the pollster.
</P>
<P>
   A tally of newspaper articles published this winter found only
six reports about homeless children, although about a fourth of the
nation's homeless are youngsters, said George White, who directs
journalism programs for the Pasadena, Calif.-based communications
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The group's report also included a quiz of journalists'
knowledge of certain youth topics: It found that while media
workers are relatively well-informed about homelessness and
parental custody laws, few realized that the juvenile crime rate is
declining and that few schools use metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest untold story is the lack of preschool education,
said former Miami Herald publisher David Lawrence Jr., who now
heads the Early Childhood Initiative Foundation at Florida
International University in Miami. Children are starting school
malnourished, abused and otherwise unprepared to learn, he said.
Yet news media often neglect to report research that shows such
facts as that of 100 first graders who can't read, 88 still will be
unable to read when they are in fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't need to tell you the future of the newspaper business
depends on people who can read,'' he said. ''Everyone including
journalists are the products of an education system that has
dismissed anything before the age of 5 as nursery school and
baby-sitting and hence undeserving of serious attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: American Society of Newspaper Editors:
http://www.asne.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0156 </TRAILER>
