<HEADLINE> New class-action suit seeks Holocaust damages from Austriancompanies  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, 
n0946nyny-
r n PM-NY--Austria-Holocaust Bjt   04-15 0421
PM-NY--Austria-Holocaust Suit, Bjt,420   
New class-action suit seeks Holocaust damages from Austrian
companies   
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A lawyer has accused 80 Austrian banks and
companies in an $18 billion lawsuit of conspiring with the Nazis to
help fuel the Holocaust and wartime slave labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed Thursday in Manhattan federal court by a New
York lawyer who specializes in cases stemming from the Holocaust.
The attorney, Edward Fagan, did not immediately return a telephone
message for comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the court documents, the Austrian banks and
companies allegedly are continuing to conceal their wrongdoing
while failing to account for assets that once belonged to Holocaust
victims, which the lawsuit seeks to certify as a class.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using forced labor, benefits came from
''Aryanization,'' a Nazi-era term used to describe the seizure of
homes, businesses and other property from owners not deemed
ethnically pure.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was greeted in Vienna, Austria, by government
officials dismayed at the global nature of a lawsuit targeting
companies that are household names -- including the Austrian Postal
Savings Bank and the Vienna Dorotheum auction house.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also names as defendants Laenderbank and Creditanstalt,
two major banks now operating under a single ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have the ambition to deal with Fagan now. Austria has
conscionably offered a gesture for the victims,'' Chancellor
Wolfgang Schuessel told Austrian state radio.
</P>
<P>
   The government has maintained it would be faster and more
expedient to settle the labor claims before dealing with other
issues, including compensation for Austrian Jews or their heirs
whose property was stolen by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Austrian government appointed Maria
Schaumayer, a former National Bank president, to work out an
agreement with former victims or their families on compensation for
former slave laborers in Nazi-ruled Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel said his government had ''full confidence'' in
Schaumayer's work.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Chancellor Susanne Riess-Passer of Joerg Haider's far-right
Freedom Party called the lawsuit ''incomprehensible,'' hinting the
attorneys involved were more interested in their fees than in the
cause they represent.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Karl-Heinz Grasser, also of the Freedom party,
spoke of ''public pressure'' being used ''as an instrument,''
adding that ''the population's patience should not be overtaxed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
