<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Builds in Yugoslavia  </HEADLINE>
By JOVANA GEC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- An opposition rally that attracted
tens of thousands has inspired the often-quarreling leaders of
Serbia's pro-democracy movement to believe they are building the
momentum needed to oust Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the harder work is yet to come, despite the surprisingly
large turnout and apparent public support for the opposition.
Milosevic's opponents face the difficult task of forcing the
autocratic president to back down and call early general elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rally was a test of the people's support and we have
passed that test,'' Zoran Djindjic, one of the opposition leaders
said after the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope that today's rally will encourage our citizens and
convince them that changes are inevitable,'' added another leader,
Vladan Batic.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition rally Friday in Belgrade's main Republic Square
attracted more than 100,000 people who defied warnings by
Milosevic's cronies to stay away. Some marched in from the
countryside on foot and evaded police checkpoints in a bold attempt
to join forces against Milosevic's grip on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was the largest opposition gathering in Belgrade
since last August and the first since the traditionally squabbling
opposition came together in January to sign a joint declaration
aimed at pushing Milosevic aside.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's government showed no willingness to back down,
responding instead with renewed attacks on the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The president's influential wife, Mirjana Markovic, accused
opposition leaders of ''treason,'' saying they want to trigger
clashes among Serbs. Serbia's Prime Minister Mirko Marjanovic
dismissed any hope of talks, describing the opposition as
''traitors' parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the country's economic and social decline, Milosevic has
ignored opposition demands for early elections, apparently fearing
he could lose them. Instead, the government has stepped up
repression, silencing independent media and cracking down on
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the opposition has failed to come up with an effective
strategy to force Milosevic into concessions. The president has
managed to retain his strong grip on power even after effectively
losing control of the southern province of Kosovo following the
78-day NATO air war against Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said the opposition will launch a major campaign,
starting next week, which will include door-to-door canvassing for
the opposition demands.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts fear that Milosevic, who is internationally isolated
because of an indictment for war crimes by the U.N. tribunal in The
Hague, Netherlands, will not give up power peacefully even if he
eventually loses the federal and municipal elections due by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also standing in the opposition's way are their traditional
rifts, which have ruined many chances of success in the past. At
the rally, Djindjic and his rival Vuk Draskovic shook hands -- a
rare public demonstration of cooperation. The handshake seemed
reluctant, though, signaling that their differences have not been
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Milan Milosevic, a columnist from the Vreme independent
weekly who is not related to the president, expressed optimism that
the opposition may be making progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''This gathering is a pledge for the opposition,'' he said.
''Things in Serbia will get clearer day after day. If this is the
beginning, we can say the end will be victorious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0240 </TRAILER>
