<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whistlers Meet in N.C. Convention  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISBURG, N.C. (AP) -- At the 27th annual International
Whistlers Convention, just pucker your lips and blow. Actually, you
don't even have to blow.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have some whistlers who whistle entirely by whistling in.
No air goes out,'' said Allen deHart, the convention founder and
assistant to the president at Louisburg College, where competition
began Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Whistle a happy tune, whistle the blues, whistle a passage from
Beethoven -- it doesn't matter what. There is competition in adult,
teen, child and ''allied arts'' divisions, the last for people who
whistle with their fingers or practice ventriloquism.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgour Shives, 84, of Vancouver, Canada, attending for the
seventh time, prefers to whistle a capella rather than with a taped
musical accompaniment as he must do at the competition, but likes
the challenge anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I get enjoyment when people hear me whistle,'' Shives said. He
planned to compete with opera accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiharu Takamoku came from Osaka, Japan, to compete. He spoke
little English but whistled clearly and handed out laminated cards
announcing the Japan Whistlers Association.
</P>
<P>
   One judge, Barry Rector of Vancouver, said whistling isn't as
popular a commercial art as it was 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whistlers that had a talent were hired by the rich and famous
to come whistle in their parlors,'' Rector said during a break in a
whistling class, where 20 or so students brushed up on their
vibrato and were counseled to keep a glass of water and lip balm
handy.
</P>
<P>
   The contest began in 1974 when the local arts festival held a
singing competition and Darrell Williams of Durham asked to whistle
his selection. He was the first whistling competition winner. He
returned the next year, bringing five or six other whistlers with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Once there were hundreds of contestants, but this year there
will be between 60 and 100 finalists; serious whistlers submitted
tapes in advance and some were eliminated. Still, if people show up
wanting to whistle, they can.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to have more whistlers because our standards were
lower,'' deHart said. ''We now have more professional whistlers,
but we never turn anybody down even though we have had some very
poor whistlers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The professional whistlers are egotistical and jealous, and
they say, 'Why do you let these whistlers in?' We say because art
should be free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 0453 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 06:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Who Faked Cancer Avoids Jail  </HEADLINE>
By BECKY BOHRER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Two years ago, after Charlene Zimmerman
told her husband and three children she was dying of cancer, people
all over Des Moines rushed to help.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, neighbors and strangers brought food for Thanksgiving
and toys for Christmas. More help came in January when the family's
house burned down. Schoolchildren collected about $1,000 and
donated clothing and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmerman, 34, didn't have cancer. She had shaved her head
to mimic the effects of chemotherapy, and the scars she displayed
weren't from biopsies -- they were self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   The lies led to a police investigation and a charge of felony
theft for taking more than $10,000 from charities and well-wishers.
On Thursday, Zimmerman entered a so-called Alford plea to a reduced
theft charge, admitting no guilt but conceding that prosecutors had
enough evidence to convict her, said her attorney, Peter Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman was ordered to pay $1,400 in restitution and was given
a deferred sentence. She will serve no jail time if she completes
two years' probation, and her record will be expunged of the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened to Charlene was the result of psychological
problems,'' Berger said. ''She truly believed she had cancer and
didn't intend to profit from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman had told neighbors in suburban Waukee, population
5,000, that she wouldn't live past a certain date. She didn't die,
her story changed and people grew suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman must write a letter of apology to be published in a
Dallas County newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, her attorney said, suffered ''multiple traumatic
events in her childhood'' and has been ''in treatment off and on
again for a long time.'' He refused to elaborate but said he and
his client had agreed to an in-depth discussion on the ABC program
''20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've heard of no hard feelings,'' said Waukee Mayor Donald
Bailey. ''It's just one of those things. If this had to happen to
get that family back on track, and Charlene personally, I'm happy
for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
