<HEADLINE> Seventh NYC Cabbie Slain This Year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A livery cab driver was shot to death early
Saturday morning, following the slaying of another driver a day
earlier. The killings, seven so far this year and 11 last year,
prompted Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to create a $5 million grant
program to help the drivers install partitions or cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has created a task force to investigate
the homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the earlier cases appeared to have been motivated by
robbery, but the driver killed Friday, Luis Francisco Perez, had
cash on him after he was killed. An arrest has been made in only
one of the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The city requires partitions on all yellow cabs and livery cars
operated by more than one driver, but individual drivers who own
their cars say the partitions are too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Since partitions were installed in yellow cabs, murders of those
drivers have been rare, Giuliani said. The last yellow cab driver
killed on the job occurred in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 41,000 livery cab drivers in the New York
area who work where yellow cabs rarely go. Only yellow cab drivers
are allowed to pick up street fares -- livery drivers are dispatched
to pick up fares -- but to make more money, many livery drivers also
pick up street fares.
</P>
</TEXT>
