<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School budgets go before NJ voters on Tuesday  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Ninety-six New Jersey school districts will
ask special voter approval on Tuesday to spend $28 million more
than they would otherwise be allowed under state-imposed budget
caps.
</P>
<P>
   That's in addition to $7.5 billion in basic local spending that
voters will be asked to approve.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 96 so-called ''second questions'' ask for extra
money for building repairs and staff, said Frank Belluscio,
spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''These aren't frivolous expenditures,'' said Belluscio. ''These
districts are retaining staff or, in some cases, going for
additional staff because they're expanding programming.''
</P>
<P>
   State law requires special voter approval for any spending
increase that exceeds a state-imposed limit of 3 percent or the
consumer price index, whichever is higher. The second questions
must specify exactly how the additional money will be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four districts will ask for extra funds to pay for
building renovations, including heating systems, roofs and security
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The second most frequent request is for more staff, with 41
districts asking voters to exceed the cap to pay for teachers,
librarians, security officers and counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Next is technology, with additional funds being requested by 24
districts. Transportation costs are included in 12 questions, while
elementary school foreign language instruction show up in seven,
according to a school boards association analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The annual school elections usually attract few voters, even
though schools cost more than any other service funded by property
taxes. Typically, less than 20 percent of registered voters show
up. Last year's turnout was 13.4 percent -- the lowest since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also choose school board members in the annual spring
elections. A total of 2,217 candidates will vie for 1,637 seats on
Tuesday, Belluscio said.
</P>
<P>
   Belluscio said school officials are generally optimistic about
getting their budgets approved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're going to see another good year,'' he said. ''The
one factor that seems to really have an impact is how well the
economy's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, voters approved 82.8 percent of school budgets -- the
second highest pass rate since the state Department of Education
began keeping track in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Voters last year also approved 72.8 percent of the separate
ballot questions, a big jump over 1998's 56.7 pass rate.
</P>
<P>
   But Lynne Strickland, director of the Garden State Coalition of
Schools, which represents about 100 suburban districts around the
state, said some school boards are worried.
</P>
<P>
   She said increasing special education and building costs are
forcing many districts to ask for significant budget increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overall budget increases are 7, 9, 11 percent,''
Strickland said.
</P>
<P>
   In Madison, Morris County, the budget proposal contains a 7.6
percent increase -- most of that due to enrollments that continue to
climb.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am worried,'' said Larry Feinsod, the district's
superintendent. ''It's tough to ask people to dig deeper in their
pockets, and the school budget is the only public budget that's
voted on. That adds more to the concern that some people will take
out their frustrations during that vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Township's proposed budget asks for a 13.5 percent
increase, which includes 40 new teachers. The district is growing
by about 400 students per year, said Jamie Savedoff,
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The Somerset County community's voters have been passing the
growing budgets, and Savedoff hopes they'll be behind it again this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year was probably our best support. The budget passed
with 69 percent of the vote. I'm not hearing too much controversy.
The community's pretty quiet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If voters reject a district's base budget, the municipal
governing body reviews it and decides whether to make cuts. In
certain cases those cuts can be appealed to the state education
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   In the districts where voters reject a special question, the
municipal governing body will review the question and decide
whether to approve any or all of the proposed spending. The
governing body's decision is final.
</P>
<P>
   Polling times vary by school district, but all are required to
be open between 5 p.m. and 9 p.m. Voters should call local school
district offices for polling times and locations.
</P>
<P>
   End Adv16
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
