<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Brokers Say Don't Panic  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Responses from some investment advisers who were
asked, ''What
should I do on Monday morning when the stock markets open?'':
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''It really depends on what an investor has in their portfolio.
But basically I'm telling my folks to stay put. People who have put
together diverse portfolios and are looking toward long-term
investment goals shouldn't have to worry too much about market
fluctuations.'' -- Vernon Lee, an independent financial planner and
head of Lee Investment Consulting in Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think stocks are way too cheap for investors to begin
selling their holdings now. History says that unless the market is
falling on an event that is extraneous to the market -- like the
outbreak of war -- it should snap back. ... But people who are
already invested may want to sell their weaker stocks, meaning
those of companies that have no earnings and were overvalued in the
first place.'' -- David Klaskin, chairman and chief executive of
Oakridge Investments in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It almost never pays to panic. People should have a
well-balanced portfolio and they should just basically be patient
with it.'' -- Jim Melcher, president of Balestra Capital Management,
a New York investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're a long-term investor, it's probably a mistake to
sell your holdings. You'll probably incur a substantial tax penalty
and, unless you're a very, very gifted person, it's unlikely that
you'll get back into the market at the right time.'' -- Burt
Greenwald, an independent mutual fund consultant in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It depends on what an investor is holding and it depends on
his objectives. ... If he's a long-term investor with long-term
goals, then my advice is to stay the course. A technology investor
who has taken on a lot of risk should stick with it if they don't
mind the volatility.'' -- Jack Piazza, a financial adviser in
Wheaton, Ill.
</P>
</TEXT>
