<HEADLINE> NJ ends criminal probe of troopers over faking records in trafficstops  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state has ended its criminal
investigation of 10 unnamed troopers who had been suspected of
falsifying records on highway traffic stops in order to conceal
patterns of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   However, these troopers who had patrolled the New Jersey
Turnpike in early 1998 remain subject to internal investigations
that could result in disciplinary steps against them.
</P>
<P>
   State Police spokesman John Hagerty said Saturday the state
attorney general's office ''completed its review and determined
that there was no criminal action, and referred it back to the
state police'' for its own proceedings. Hagerty said none of the
troopers had been suspended or assigned to changes in duty as a
result of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A state grand jury in April 1999 indicted troopers John Hogan
and James Kenna on charges of police misconduct for falsifying
reports and for illegally stopping vehicles and searching
occupants. The allegations included efforts to misrepresent the
race of the motorists they had stopped in order to conceal the fact
they were targeting minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Kenna and Hogan had been involved in the April 1998 shooting of
three minority men during a traffic stop on the turnpike, which led
to their indictment last September by a different grand jury on
charges of attempted murder. Hogan and Kenna claimed their opened
fire because the van the men were in was backing up to strike them.
</P>
<P>
   The suspended troopers still await trial on both sets of
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   As state investigators were digging into the turnpike shooting,
they reviewed the traffic stop records of Hogan, Kenna and other
troopers in the Moorestown and Cranbury barracks assigned to patrol
the turnpike. The misconduct indictment against Hogan and Kenna
arose from this separate inquiry and concerned traffic stops
conducted in the three months before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   First Assistant Attorney General Paul Zoubek at the time said
the inquiry would continue. It was later reported the traffic stops
of 10 other troopers were being scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan was charged with 17 counts of falsifying or tampering with
records, Kenna with eight counts. Both were also indicted on two
counts each of misconduct. They face up to 10 years in prison and
$100,000 in fines for each of the counts of official misconduct.
The falsifying records charges carry a maximum penalty of up to 18
months in prison and $7,500 in fines for each count.
</P>
<P>
   State Police Superintendent Col. Carson Dunbar met with members
of the state's Black Ministers Council Friday, assuring them racial
profiling had been fully addressed. ''Those few who have also
caused problems in the past also know this is a new day,'' Dunbar
told the ministers. He did not tell them the criminal probe of
other troopers had been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer said New Jersey has done more
''than any other state or the federal government to prohibit the
practice of racial profiling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1259 </TRAILER>
