<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Squatters Vow Defiance  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Squatters illegally occupying hundreds
of white-owned farms will continue their takeovers, defying a High
Court ruling and a government appeal for them to leave the farms, a
leader of the occupations said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there are human rights, we have right to our land ... and
that must be respected,'' Chenjerai Hunzvi, head of the National
Liberation War Veterans Association told about 500 cheering
supporters at the ruling party's headquarters in Harare. ''The
redistribution of land must be speeded up.''
</P>
<P>
   Police, meanwhile, resisted a court order to oust the armed
black squatters from white-owned farms and instead mounted a
massive security operation in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   As police helicopters swooped overhead, officers erected
roadblocks at the approaches to the city center. There they
searched cars and buses for weapons. Riot police also deployed
across the city ''in case there might be people who would like to
cause trouble,'' said Assistant Commissioner Emmanuel Chimwanda,
the operation commander.
</P>
<P>
   The roadblocks left hundreds of vehicles stalled on main
highways leading to the city center where Hunzvi addressed militant
ex-guerrillas of Zimbabwe's liberation war from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's 4,000 white-owned farms comprise about a third of the
country's productive farmland, while millions of blacks are
landless and impoverished. Since the end of February, thousands of
squatters armed with clubs, axes and guns have invaded at least 900
white-owned farms and demanded the farmers sign away their land.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe has called the actions a justified
protest against inequality in land ownership. Some squatters have
admitted being paid by ruling party activists.
</P>
<P>
   Police will appeal a High Court order for them to evict the
squatters, the state-controlled Herald newspaper reported Saturday.
Police have said they lack the resources to act against the armed
invaders and that doing so could end in violence.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the High Court made its ruling Thursday, Vice
President Joseph Msika asked the squatters to abandon the occupied
farms and said the government wanted to end the standoff amicably.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, Hunzvi told his cheering and singing followers
that he did not respect any court ruling that he believed was
unfair. He said he could not control the actions of squatters
claiming their ''motherland, their soil.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the white farmers, he said: ''The land has been left in their
hands too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Although police complain that they lack sufficient personnel and
equipment, Saturday's mobilization of thousands of officers showed
they can bring downtown Harare to a virtual standstill. The
operation effectively sealed off the city center for several hours,
leaving parking lots and bus parks mostly empty during usually busy
shopping hours.
</P>
<P>
   Chimwanda said there were no reports of violence. He explained
the security campaign as an anti-crime effort and a measure to
avert possible political unrest ahead of upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, 15 people were injured in downtown Harare when
ruling party militants and men claiming to be ex-guerrillas
attacked opposition protesters with iron bars, clubs, bricks and
wire whips.
</P>
<P>
   The Movement for Democratic Change, the main opposition group,
said it had no rallies or protests planned in Harare on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1335 </TRAILER>
