<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estate used by anti-abortion leader Randall Terry is for sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, N.Y. (AP) -- The 116-acre estate used by one of the
nation's most prominent anti-abortion leaders and his followers is
on the market as past court judgments from protests mount.
</P>
<P>
   The rural home used for years by Randall Terry, founder of
Operation Rescue, is valued at $499,000. Terry, who is working in
Vermont, is considering a run for U.S. Senate now being pursued by
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The estate is for sale in the wake of legal action against
Terry, reported the Binghamton Press &AMP; Sun-Bulletin. Terry, in town
for his syndicated radio show, Randall Terry Live, wouldn't
comment.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Cindy Terry, who owns the property, said the sale is
not an attempt to shield assets from creditors. The six-bedroom
house is too big for her and her children since Terry left, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband left me in August. Me and my two daughters live at
the home, and it's too big a place,'' she said. The six-bedroom
Victorian 15 miles east of Binghamton, N.Y., had been used for
retreats for Terry and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a guest house, in-ground pool, basketball and tennis
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Terry had sought protection from opposing organizations and
creditors by filing for bankruptcy in November 1998. He claimed he
had $1.7 million in debts, mostly civil judgments won by women's
groups and abortion rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the property comes after a federal bankruptcy court
in March denied a motion to dismiss a claim by Terry's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if it's an attempt to raise money to settle (the
case) or if it's an attempt to avoid it being a part of his
bankruptcy,'' said attorney Peter Orville of nearby Vestal, N.Y. He
represents a number of women's groups across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Terry moved to Montpelier, Vt., where he heads Loyal Opposition,
which lobbies against legislation proposing same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Terry was ordered in 1988 to pay $50,000 in a lawsuits for
blocking access to abortion clinics. In 1989, he was one of three
people ordered to pay a $282,610 fine for violating an injunction
against blocking abortion clinics. The state also filed three tax
liens in 1994 and 1995 totaling $6,831.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1401 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Furor over power plant proposed for Hudson ValleyBy MICHAEL HILL Associated Press Writer </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, N.Y. (AP) -- Picture this: a Hudson River School painting
portraying lush green hills, vast blue skies and a 1080-megawatt
power plant.
</P>
<P>
   That dissonant image helps explain the controversy over the
proposed Athens Generating Project.
</P>
<P>
   Many opponents dislike the idea of building a power plant a
couple of miles from the historic banks of the Hudson River -- along
a stretch of land master painter Frederick Church gazed at from his
hilltop home named Olana. With a crucial ruling on the proposal due
soon from New York, one issue under review revolves around the
plant's impact on that historic view.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E Generating wants to build a $500 million plant fueled
primarily by natural gas in Athens, a quaint, modest river town
about 30 miles south of Albany in rural Greene County.
</P>
<P>
   The Athens plant would sell its electricity wholesale through
New York's newly-deregulated power market. Dan Whyte, the company's
director of government relations, said the plant will serve eastern
New York. If approved, it would be the first major power plant to
be authorized by the state in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Athens proposal has been under review for more than a year --
dogged by controversy for much of the time. A focus of the furor is
located some four to five miles south of the proposed site, across
the river at the Olana State Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   Church chose this hilltop perch to begin building his grand,
Moorish-style home in 1870. The popular tourist attraction still
provides a panoramic view of the Hudson Valley -- albeit one
considerably more developed than the 19th century vista known to
Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Athens plant would only be visible from portions of the
Olana property. However, it would be more noticeable with plumes of
steam rising from its smokestacks.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that have joined the fray against the Athens plant
include Friends of Olana and Scenic Hudson. Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan in November called for a U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
review. And Pataki's parks commissioner, Bernadette Castro, wrote
last year that the Athens plant would have an ''adverse effect'' on
the valley's historic and cultural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's only one Olana in the state of New York,'' said Carl
Dworkin, a lawyer for a group opposing the plant called Citizens
for the Hudson Valley. ''You want to be real careful in what you
put there and only sacrifice if there is a real dying need.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents claim the plant could be located somewhere else,
although the company cites the proximity of gas and power lines to
the Athens site as one of its best features.
</P>
<P>
   Whyte said the PG&AMP;E Generating has made a number of changes
since Castro wrote her letter -- things like changing the plant's
color from white to brown and lowering planned smokestack heights.
The company has also agreed to plant trees at Olana to act as
''vegetative screening.''
</P>
<P>
   Whyte noted the conclusion of two state hearing officers who
reported last fall that the visual impact of the Athens plant would
be acceptable since it would be a ''relatively minor component of
the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hearing officers forwarded their findings to the state
Board on Electric Generation Siting and the Environment. The board
is due to make a decision on Athens by April 30, although the
deadline has been pushed back before.
</P>
<P>
   The plant proposal also faces reviews by the state Department of
Environmental Conservation and the Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The state siting board will look at whole a range of issues,
including the plant's larger environmental impact.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents believe the company's plan to draw water from the
Hudson River to cool the plant could endanger shad coming up the
river to spawn. Theresa Rose Hanczor, an attorney at Riverkeeper,
is concerned Athens would fail to use the best technology available
-- a ''dry cooling'' system that relies on far less river water.
</P>
<P>
   Whyte said Athens would require far less water than five power
plants already on the river currently use.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you really care about the river, you want this plant
because it will displace the other plants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is supported by local residents who see the plant as
an economic engine for a rural county where the unemployment rate
has lately been above 6 percent. PG&AMP;E has sweetened the deal with a
package that includes a $3 million trust for the town, $250,000 for
computer science at local schools and a block of wholesale power
for the town and county.
</P>
<P>
   Arlin Anderson of the county chamber of commerce claims that
despite a high-profile opposition campaign, a silent majority backs
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opponents have definitely made their voice heard a lot
louder. However, they are the minority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said a mailed questionnaire to local residents showed
support running overwhelmingly for the plant. Responses to that
mailing also included a few death threats, underscoring local
tensions over the proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1413 </TRAILER>
