<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislature moves to outlaw gift-giving to jurors  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A bill is headed toward passage in the state
Legislature to make it a crime for people involved in trials to
give money or other gratuities to jurors, as Abraham Hirschfeld did
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was in direct response to Hirschfeld's gifts of
$2,500 to each of the 10 members of a jury in New York City which
deadlocked over whether he was guilty of tax fraud.
</P>
<P>
   When Hirschfeld was tried later in the year in connection with
an alleged murder-for-hire plot, a state Supreme Court justice
barred him from paying jurors in that trial after it ended.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld's lawyer Arthur Aidala argued that there was no legal
basis in New York for Justice Carol Berkman to issue that order and
that Hirschfeld was free to give money or other gifts to anyone he
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the legislation this year in Albany affirms that
there is currently no prohibition in state law to paying jurors
like Hirschfeld did, lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. James Lack, a Nassau County Republican who chairs his
chamber's judiciary committee, said the state Office of Court
Administration was ''absolutely, totally taken aback by the vacuum
Mr. Hirschfeld capitalized on'' last year to make his payments.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation proposed this year by the Office of Court
Administration would make it a Class A misdemeanor for someone to
give a gratuity to a juror in a civil or criminal action in which
that person was a party.
</P>
<P>
   A Class A misdemeanor carries a fine up to $1,000 and up to a
year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Court administrators said payments like those by Hirschfeld, a
quirky millionaire who made his money building open-air parking
garages, undermine the legal system by giving the appearance that
defendants are rewarding jurors for deciding cases in their favor.
No compensation should be made to jurors past the pay they receive
for serving, administrators said.
</P>
<P>
   David Bookstaver, a spokesman for the Office of Court
Administration, said top court officials were ''delighted'' the
bill passed the state Senate on April 3. It is now in committee the
state Assembly, but with Codes Committee Chairman Joseph Lentol and
Judiciary Committee Chairwoman Helene Weinstein as its prime
sponsors, it is expected to win final passage in that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will preserve the dignity of the court process,''
Bookstaver said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the spokesman, gift-giving to jurors has not been
banned earlier in New York because court administrators knew of no
instances where it had occurred before Hirschfeld's payments to
jurors at his tax fraud trial.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated attempts since April 3 to elicit comment from
Hirschfeld, who is running for U.S. Senate this year, failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1415 </TRAILER>
