<HEADLINE> AM-NY--Syringe Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, 235  </HEADLINE>
Doctor attacks woman with a syringe outside hospital
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A Westchester County doctor attacked a nurse by
stabbing her six times with a syringe outside a Bronx hospital,
police reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Pack, 44, a resident of the posh Westchester
community of Chappaqua, reportedly had been romantically involved
with the woman, who was pregnant, police and television reports
said. He was charged with assault, said police spokesman Alan
Krawitz.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old woman, who suffered five stab wounds to the leg
and one to the buttocks, was taken to Montefiore Hospital. She was
attacked just outside that hospital on Friday at about 8 p.m. and
was listed in stable condition on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor was arrested minutes after the attack near the scene
at 210th Street and Rochambeau Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Pack is married and the syringe attack apparently was his
attempt to abort the 6-week-old fetus by injecting the woman with a
fluid -- possibly a substance used to induce labor or cause an
abortion, local television reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Pack waited for her by the parking garage at East
210th Street, then lunged at her, threw her to the ground and
yelled that he would give her an abortion, according to WPIX
television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
