<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Challenged  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- With more than half the votes counted,
Rauf Denktash led the race for president of the self-declared
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus on Saturday, but was short of
the majority necessary to avoid a run-off.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash gathered close to 44 percent of votes, while his main
contender, Prime Minister Dervis Eroglu, had 30 percent, according
to the Turkish Cypriot Higher Election Board. The results were
based on a count of 56 percent of the ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, I'll win,'' Denktash said of the initial results.
''Worst comes to worst it'll be in the second round,'' he said on
Bayrak state television.
</P>
<P>
   The election for president of the north half of Cyprus -- the
Turkish half -- comes just a month before Turkish Cypriot and Greek
Cypriot leaders gather in New York for another attempt to find a
solution to the island's division.
</P>
<P>
   The impending talks are expected to help boost support for
Denktash's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had it been at another time, it wouldn't have been so
important to choose Denktash. But he must finish this peace deal,''
said 25-year-old Gurhum Umut, who said he was voting for the first
time because he was worried that Denktash would need every vote.
</P>
<P>
   After polls closed, a preliminary tally showed that 76 percent
of the electorate voted.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash, 75, established the Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus in 1983 and is leader of his community of 200,000. His
self-declared state is only recognized by Turkey, which maintains
some 30,000 troops on the island.
</P>
<P>
   However, he faced a strong challenge from Eroglu, who has built
support through his role as prime minister and the distribution of
social assistance. Eroglu forced Denktash into a run-off in the
last election in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''Denktash hasn't solved the issue in decades. You think he will
now?'' said Mevlut Haci Mevlut, an Eroglu supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash called on voters to cast their ballots for him, saying
''let's not wait for a second round.''
</P>
<P>
   Most seemed to believed Denktash would again be forced into a
run-off against Eroglu.
</P>
<P>
   ''And if he doesn't win in this round, he may have difficulty in
a run-off because all other candidates could unite against him,''
said Yusuf Kanli, an expert on Cypriot politics.
</P>
<P>
   Six other candidates were running Saturday, including five
left-wing candidates. A second round of voting will be held April
22 if no candidate gains more than 50 percent of the vote Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of peace has become more urgent because of the
European Union's membership talks with Cyprus. Turkish Cypriots
want a settlement to be reached as soon as possible so the two
sides can enter the EU simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been divided into Turkish and Greek sections since
the 1974 Turkish invasion which came in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
