<HEADLINE> India: Clinton a Help in Kashmir  </HEADLINE>
By BINOO JOSHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMMU, India (AP) -- President Clinton's visit last month to
India and Pakistan helped reduce tensions between the two nuclear
rivals over the disputed territory of Kashmir, India's defense
minister said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister George Fernandes said during a visit to Jammu,
the winter capital of Jammu-Kashmir state, that India would be open
to Pakistan's offer to restart talks if Islamabad continues to
scale down attacks on Indian forces in the Himalayan territory.
</P>
<P>
   While saying there had been no change in ''Pakistan's attitude''
on Kashmir, Fernandes noted that ''the number of rounds fired by
Pakistan across the cease-fire line has gone down after Clinton's
visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension had escalated between India and Pakistan before
Clinton's visit to the subcontinent in late March. Armies on both
sides exchanged heavy gunfire on an almost daily basis across the
cease-fire line dividing Kashmir between the hostile neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan was hoping Clinton would agree to mediate in its
Kashmir dispute with India, but Clinton ruled out any such
participation unless both sides agreed and asked Pakistan to
respect the cease-fire line. He also pressed both sides to resume
talks.
</P>
<P>
   India rejects any third party intervention and says it wants to
settle the dispute directly with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India has accused Pakistan of training and arming Kashmiri
militants. Pakistan says it only provides moral and diplomatic
support to the Islamic rebels fighting a secessionist war in
Indian-held Kashmir since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   An Egyptian newspaper on Saturday quoted Gen. Pervez Musharraf,
Pakistan's military ruler, as saying that any solution to the
Kashmir issue ''should take into consideration the hopes of the
people of Kashmir according to U.N. resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These resolutions are the key for normalizing relations
between India and Pakistan,'' the Al-Ahram newspaper quoted
Musharraf as saying. He arrived in Cairo on Saturday for talks with
Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan wants residents of Kashmir to be allowed to vote on
whether to join India or Pakistan, as outlined in decades-old U.N.
resolutions. India opposes the idea.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have fought two wars over control of Kashmir
since they won independence from Britain in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   A dialogue between the two countries was interrupted after India
detected hundreds of armed fighters occupying mountainous peaks in
the Kargil sector in Indian-held Kashmir in May last year.
</P>
<P>
   India said the fighters were Pakistani army soldiers and Afghan
mercenaries and carried out massive ground and air attacks for 11
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions were diffused after Pakistan asked the fighters to pull
back. Islamabad said the infiltrators were Kashmiri rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, the army seized 230 pounds of a demolition
explosive in Kashmir in what was considered to be the biggest haul
of RDX in the past two years, Press Trust of India news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   RDX -- so powerful that two pounds of it can blow up an aircraft
-- is often used by Islamic guerrillas fighting Indian security
forces in Kashmir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1447 </TRAILER>
