<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Air Force To Charge Officer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Air Force will charge an officer with
dereliction of duty and will reprimand five others for their parts
in the death of a suburban Cincinnati recruit during a training
exercise, The Cincinnati Enquirer reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Airman Micah J. Schindler, 18, collapsed Sept. 10 after a
5.8-mile march during recruit training at Lackland Air Force Base
in San Antonio, Texas. He died two days later.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force general in charge of training at the base and six
other officers flew to Cincinnati on Friday to deliver their final
case report to Schindler's parents, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler's father, Michael Schindler, said he is upset no
criminal charges will be filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe the people have been held accountable to the
degree they should be,'' he said. ''Now I feel they didn't and
don't care about Micah.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force considers its charges in the case ''nonjudicial
punishments.''
</P>
<P>
   A noncommissioned officer will be charged with dereliction of
duty for failing to properly assess Schindler's condition after he
vomited during a dinner break less than an hour before he
collapsed, Air Force officials said. The maximum punishment
includes reduction in rank and 30 days in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Two officers and three noncommissioned officers will get letters
of reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force wouldn't release the names of the officers.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case last week, a Marine captain based a Camp
LeJeune, N.C., was given a reprimand and fined for his role in the
July 7 death of a reservist during a training hike.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Victor Arana, 28, of Chicago was found guilty of
dereliction of duty and failure to obey an order. He was leading
the 8-mile conditioning hike in 80-degree heat after which Lance
Cpl. Giuseppe ''Joey'' Leto, 21, of New Milford, Conn., collapsed
and died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
