<DOCNO> APW20000415.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright in Kazakstan for Talks  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASTANA, Kazakstan (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
reached agreement with the president of this central Asian nation
on a wide range of topics Saturday, including a pledge from the
Kazak leader to tighten weapons exports.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a result of our expanded discussion, it is evident that we
have a multifaceted relationship that deals with many areas of
common interest,'' Albright said after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The two touched on one subject that clearly irritated President
Nursultan Nazarbayev -- the handling of the case of officials who
sold 40 Soviet-built MiG-21 jet fighters to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officials, the Kazak military chief of staff, was
acquitted of abuse of office in connection with the case, while a
presidential adviser was convicted of smuggling but immediately
given amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, the defense minister and the national security
chief, resigned when the sale was reported last August, but were
later reappointed to lower-level posts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the trial results nor the reappointments pleased
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously had a discussion and I did in fact express our
surprise and disappointment about the outcome of the trial and the
transfer of the two people discussed,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarbayev angrily defended reappointing the two officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were demoted to lower-level jobs and that was their
punishment,'' Nazarbayev said. ''I don't think it's the
responsibility of the U.S. secretary of state to decide who should
be appointed to what position in southern Kazakstan.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Kazakstan, a country of 16 million people, has taken
measures to tighten export controls to prevent such arms deals in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was pleased that Kazakstan had agreed to lift a cap on
oil exports, imposed last year by the government to keep oil at
home after Kazak and foreign oil companies sold mostly on foreign
markets for higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was pleased with the decision to eliminate the cap on oil
exports,'' Albright said. ''We view it as a signal of Kazakstan's
intention to improve the climate of both foreign and domestic
investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright announced a number of U.S.-funded initiatives designed
to support democracy and human rights in Kazakstan. They include
Internet access and training, support for independent media, civics
education for Kazak youth and support for public organizations.
</P>
<P>
   She also unveiled a plan to combat terrorism, including the
strengthening of coordination by security policy makers, and
exchange of information among experts in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarbayev and leaders of other Central Asian nations have
claimed they need to maintain a tight grip on power because of the
danger of Islamic extremism spilling over into their regions. Such
fears have been stoked by the radical Taliban movement taking over
most of Afghanistan, which borders on the former Soviet republics
of Uzbekistan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
   Kazak authorities said last fall they had to battle Islamic
militants in the south of the country, while Uzbekistan had a
series of bombings in February that were blamed on opposition
Islamic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, several hundred Islamic fighters raided Kyrgyzstan,
engaging government troops and holding a dozen hostages for more
than two months.
</P>
<P>
   It was Albright's first visit to Central Asia in more than three
years in office. Following her talks with Nazarbayev, Albright was
expected to meet with the leaders of nongovernment organizations.
She planned to go to Kyrgyzstan on Sunday and visit Uzbekistan on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright on Friday visited Ukraine, where she urged officials to
set a definite date for the closure of the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
