<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Revives Old Play  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Playwright Arthur Miller's first Broadway
production, ''The Man Who Had All the Luck,'' was so poorly
received it closed after just four performances.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1944, when the famed author of such classics as
''The Crucible'' and ''Death of a Salesman'' was 29.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Man Who Had All the Luck'' hasn't been seen in America
since -- until now.
</P>
<P>
   The former resident director of Broadway's ''The Lion King'' is
reviving the early work for a limited run at Los Angeles' Ivy
Substation theater.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Fields said he's long been drawn to the play, a fable about
a young man who has the unlucky fortune of getting everything his
heart desires.
</P>
<P>
   ''The power of Miller's young voice astounded me,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Miller, the playwright said he was won over by Fields'
passion for the play, set to run from Saturday night through May
21.
</P>
<P>
   ''He seemed to know what the play was meant to accomplish,''
Miller said. ''Enthusiasm deserves reward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
