<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300 rally outside quiet Statehouse to defend abortion rights, backcandidates  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- About 300 activists fearing a threat to
abortion rights marched downtown here Saturday and staged a
cheerful Statehouse rally despite a continuous drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Statehouse was locked and closed as usual on
weekends, the rally nevertheless carried political weight as
Democratic candidates for seats in Congress walked with or spoke to
the group to advance their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The two men competing for the Democratic nomination for U.S.
Senate, Jon Corzine and former Gov. Jim Florio, gave brief speeches
beneath a canopy as activists listened, cheered, chanted and
huddled under dripping umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's campaign had promoted his appearance; Corzine's kept
his quiet. Most in the crowd showed no real preference for either,
pleased that both firmly opposed restrictions on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The political heat turned up for Cherry Hill Mayor Susan Bass
Levin, a longtime Democratic activist on the New Jersey political
scene who is challenging an anti-abortion congressman in southern
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   After toying with various possible races over the years, Bass
Levin finally pulled the trigger last week when she filed to run
against U.S. Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, in the 3rd district,
which covers parts of Camden, Burlington and Ocean counties.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Levin has said a key to her campaign will be to target
Saxton for his abortion views, and she tapped into that tactic
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''My opponent speaks proudly of the fact that for 25 years, he
has voted to deny us our right to choose,'' Bass Levin said to a
wave of booing. ''We must make the difference. We must do it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW New Jersey president Elizabeth Volz said, ''This woman has
the fight, she has the energy, she has the money. Let's get him
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Maryanne Connelly also spoke to build support in her
Democratic primary in the 7th district, where she is vying with
seven others to replace U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights.
Franks is stepping down to run for U.S. Senate, but neither he nor
most of the Republicans running to replace him in the northern New
Jersey district are known for opposing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Female ralliers young and old said they feel abortion rights are
under constant threat.
</P>
<P>
   D.D. Ables, 79, of Basking Ridge, said she recalls the years
before the U.S. Supreme Court struck down abortion bans in 1973.
''It was done, and it certainly improved a lot once we got legal.
And it certainly improved a lot once we got free access to Planned
Parenthood clinics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very firmly that people should have a right to choose
whether to have a baby or not. I prefer that they not have an
abortion,'' Able said. But, she added, ''We have got to show our
support for people who really want to stand up for legislation that
will keep the right available for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dillon, 20, of Elizabeth said she opposes laws to restrict
abortion access for teen-agers, adding that for many a requirement
to notify parents before an abortion is the same as an outright ban
on the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes it harder because kids have other things to deal with
other than fearing their parents because they're pregnant,'' Dillon
said. ''It is really putting risks on teen-age girls who are
pregnant because of rape or incest or because they were careless or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Ani Desilets, 23, of Roselle, said activism and rallies are
important ''as long as we have conservative men and right-wing
Christians in power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1549 </TRAILER>
