<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine tops $10 million in spending on Senate primary  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- How much does a seat in the U.S. Senate cost?
For New Jersey millionaire Jon S. Corzine, the price tag has
already topped $10 million, just in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   The former chairman of Goldman Sachs reported Saturday that he
spent more than $6.6 million in the first three months of 2000, the
vast majority from his own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to the $3.2 million he spent in the final half of 1999,
plus a smaller amount before that, and Corzine is on pace to spend
a record amount in a Senate primary.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey primary is June 6. Corzine is spending at least
$1 million a week on advertising in the 12 weeks leading up to
primary day, which means he could easily top $20 million in
spending just during the primary.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent for the Democratic nomination, former Gov. Jim
Florio, reported spending $346,000 in the first three months of
2000. Added to his prior spending of $573,000, he is still under $1
million in expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns on Saturday provided summaries of financial
reports that had to be in the mail by day's end to the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, worth an estimated $300 million, has not said how much
of his own money he is willing to spend on race for Senate. He has
thus far loaned his campaign about $8 million from his own pockets.
At this pace of personal spending, Corzine is approaching levels
never seen outside California.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Checchi spent nearly $39 million in losing his
party's 1998 primary for California governor.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Michael Huffington spent $30 million in California's
1994 Senate race, only to lose to Democrat Dianne Feinstein. Like
Corzine, he had a contested primary; unlike Corzine, Huffington
spent well under $10 million on the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., paid for his successful 1998
campaign largely with $11 million in loans he guaranteed against
his personal fortune. About $7 million of that was spent to win the
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Though bankrolling his campaign mostly from his own wealth,
Corzine is also raising funds from others. His campaign said
Corzine raised about $905,000 in the first three months of 2000 and
$2.3 million overall since entering the race. He had about $557,000
on hand as of March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Florio raised $302,000 in the first three months of 2000 and had
$961,000 on hand on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Florio has made an issue of Corzine's wealth, saying it
threatens ''to make this not a primary contest but an auction.''
</P>
<P>
   But a recent Qunnipiac College poll found that most Democratic
voters are not turned off by either Corzine's wealth or his
willingness to use it for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, the people of New Jersey will care more about the
billions that Jim Florio has taken out of their pockets than the
millions Jon Corzine has taken out of his,'' said Steven Goldstein,
one of Corzine's two campaign managers.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the $2.8 billion tax increase Florio enacted
as governor, which led to his ouster after one term. Corzine said
earlier in the campaign that he would not attack Florio for the tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Florio spokesman Jim Lanard responded, ''Jim Florio has
committed his career to fighting for children, working families and
seniors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1557 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Software Glitch at H&AMP;R Block  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- An error in an electronic tax-filing
program that misread intervals of $1,000 as intervals of $1 has
left some H&AMP;R Block customers owing money to the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block has told about 3,000 of its income tax customers that
because of the error, they didn't pay enough money to the IRS and
they will have to send a check, a company spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The problem affects only customers who owed more than $1,000,
filed returns electronically on the company's Tax Cut software or
online and had authorized the IRS to take the payments directly out
of their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The program misread the comma in amounts of $1,000 or more owed
as the end of the line, meaning $1,000 was read as $1.
</P>
<P>
   Affected taxpayers were notified by overnight letter and e-mail
Friday that they would have to use regular mail to send their
payments to the IRS, said Neil Getzlow, a spokesman for the Kansas
City-based company. He said the software problem had been
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are working with the IRS to ensure that they will not face
any penalties,'' Getzlow said. ''In the unlikely event that
happens, H&AMP;R Block will take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRS said affected taxpayers should include the letter from
Block when mailing their payments.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 million people use the company or its software to
prepare their tax returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1611 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Bids 'Impossible'  </HEADLINE>
By AARON FAVILA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISABELA, Philippines (AP) -- It is impossible to meet the demands
of Philippine rebels who want to trade hostages for Arab terrorists
jailed in the United States, Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What kind of a demand is this?'' Mercado asked. ''We can't
even consider them.'' He said negotiators should continue trying to
convince the Muslim extremists to free the 29 people they were
holding at a jungle base in Basilan, about 545 miles south of
Manila.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to President Joseph Estrada, the Abu Sayyaf group
listed Ramzi Yousef, the mastermind of the 1993 bombing of the
World Trade Center in New York, and Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman,
imprisoned for conspiring to blow up New York City landmarks, among
those they wanted freed.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Franklin Drilon said the rebel demand was ''out
of this world'' and urged the government to reject it outright.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels seized more than 50 people from two schools in
Basilan province after attacking an army outpost on March 20. They
were still holding 31 last week. But they freed two children Friday
after Robin Padilla, a popular movie actor helping negotiate the
hostages' release, visited their stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla met relatives of the remaining hostages Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry, I was not able to free all,'' Padilla told the
relatives waiting at a Catholic center in Basilan's capital,
Isabela.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf is the smaller but more radical of two Muslim groups
fighting for an independent Islamic state in the southern
Philippines. The group has been blamed for numerous attacks on
Christians, including the abduction of foreign missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Saturday, officials raised a Philippine flag in a
major Muslim separatist camp captured after days of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Brig. Gen. Emmanuel Teodosio said Camp Bilal, in Munai
town in southern Lanao del Norte province, fell Friday afternoon.
Up to 500 rebels fled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for the camp, which began on April 8, left three
soldiers dead and 18 marines wounded. An undetermined number of
guerrillas were killed, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   The camp belonged to the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, the
larger rebel group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1614 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0112 </DOCNO>
