<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D'Alema's Market Investments Decried  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Responding to attacks from right-wing opponents,
Premier Massimo D'Alema defended his stock market investments and
noted that he recently took a loss, Italian newspapers reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   During the final hours of campaigning for regional elections,
D'Alema waved a March 31 bank statement in front of reporters on
Friday, the newspapers said. The statement showed that his market
investments had resulted in a loss of about $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is supposed to be my conflict of interest?'' D'Alema
asked. The exact nature of the investments was not revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Maurizio Gasparri of the right-wing National Alliance,
said he had asked magistrates to investigate to see if D'Alema's
investments constituted conflicts of interest for the government's
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The political sparring comes ahead of regional elections Sunday
that could influence D'Alema's political future. Coming roughly a
year ahead of parliamentary elections, the outcome of balloting is
seen as a measure of support for D'Alema's center-left bloc and for
chief rival Silvio Berlusconi's conservative alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Within D'Alema's own coalition, there has been criticism of the
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be inopportune, make that highly inopportune, that a
minister uses information to his own personal advantage,'' said
Arturo Parisi, whose Democrats have been part of the coalition
infighting which has scarred D'Alema's government.
</P>
<P>
   A few ministers in the Cabinet also have stock investments,
Milan daily Il Corriere della Sera reported Saturday. A proposed
law prohibiting ministers and Cabinet undersecretaries from
investing in the stock market has been bogged down in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was a day of reflection for some three-quarters of
Italy's population eligible to vote for presidents and assemblies
for 15 of the nation's 20 regions.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign barely touched on issues that fall under the domain
of regional officials, such as health and transportation services.
Instead the focus was on D'Alema, a former Communist who has been
running the country for a year and a half, and Berlusconi, the
media magnate who -- as he did when he launched his conservative
movement in the early 1990s -- has teamed up with former
neo-fascists and autonomy-seeking advocates of the affluent north.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi's economic empire includes Italy's biggest private TV
networks as well as publishing, real estate and advertising
interests. He has long been criticized for possible conflict of
interests between business and politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1622 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-cop Convicted in Fastball Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- A former police officer was convicted of
soliciting assault for giving a 10-year-old Little League pitcher
$2 to bean another youngster with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated only two hours Friday before convicting Shawn
Patrick Phillips of misdemeanor charges of corruption of minors and
solicitation to commit simple assault.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, 28, a former part-time officer in East Penn Township
and Coaldale, faces up to three months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Carbon County Detective Joseph Pampanin testified that Phillips
admitted asking the pitcher to hit a batter last May.
</P>
<P>
   The boy hit a 10-year-old in the leg, dropping him to the ground
and bruising him. Four days later Phillips gave the youngster $2
for the job, Pampanin said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips testified that he was only joking about beaning the
other player and that he gave the boy $2 for listening to his
pitching tips
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not detail a motive.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was fired in December for unrelated reasons, said
Coaldale Police Chief Jim Strauss.
</P>
</TEXT>
