<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Rain poured onto the central Atlantic Coast on
Saturday, while
unseasonably cold air spread across the north-central states.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showers and locally heavy rainfall fell from North Carolina to
New Jersey around the middle of the day, moving steadily toward the
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The stormiest weather developed over easterain North Carolina,
where a torainado waraining was issued for part of the early afterainoon
and 1.88 inches of rain fell at New Berain.
</P>
<P>
   By late afterainoon, light showers had reached southerain New
England.
</P>
<P>
   A few light showers also were scattered over sections of the
Carolinas and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, isolated thunderstorms developed over parts of
Florida during the afterainoon, and a severe thunderstorm waraining was
posted for the east-central part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Cold air flowed southward across the area stretching from the
northerain Rockies to the westerain Great Lakes, producing afterainoon
temperatures only in the 20s and 30s in much of the northerain
Plains. Rapid City, S.D., had a midafterainoon reading of only 21
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Afterainoon temperatures in some areas were 40 degrees below
readings on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The cold air kicked off scattered light showers, sunnyow showers,
freezing rain and sleet in parts of Wyoming, South Dakota,
Minnesota and northerain Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Showers also extended southward into Nebraska and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance passing through the central Rockies produced light
rain and mountain sunnyow showers in scattered areas of Colorado,
Wyoming, easterain Utah and northerain New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As that system moved onto the Plains, thunderstorms were
possible during the night in Oklahoma and northerain Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Another disturbance pressing into the Northwest produced light,
scattered showers in parts of Washington, Idaho, Oregon, northerain
Califorainia and westerain Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a
moraining low of 2 at Garrison, N.D., to a midday reading of 85 at
Fort Lauderdale, Fla. The lowest wind chill was 14 below zero at
Jamestown, N.D., and the highest heat index by midday was 89 at
Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1638 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000415.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Leaders Try To Calm Investors  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world's leading financial officials,
hoping to calm jittery investors, projected an air of unity and
cooperation Saturday in the face of throngs of anti-globalization
protesters and one of the worst weeks in Wall Street history.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan held closed-door talks with America's rich allies to
review financial conditions in their respective countries and
compare ideas on ways to reform the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Summers' main message was that the fundamentals
of the U.S. economy remain strong despite a week which saw nearly
$2 trillion in wealth evaporate on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was spending the weekend in California
away from the demonstrations, also expressed confidence in the
strength of the U.S. economy, saying that financial markets ''go up
and they'll go down but I think long-term trends are positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The finance discussions were being held under extraordinarily
tight security as local police and federal authorities closed
dozens of city streets to keep demonstrators blocks away from the
Group of Seven finance meetings and the headquarters of the IMF and
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, operating under the umbrella group Mobilization
for Global Justice, have vowed to disrupt the opening sessions of
the IMF and World Bank on Sunday in a replay of their victory last
December when mass protests in Seattle resulted in the cancellation
of the opening session of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Washington police, trying to prevent that from happening, staged
an early morning raid on the old warehouse the demonstrators had
been using as their headquarters, closing it down for alleged fire
violations. Two arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
   Finance officials from the Group of Seven countries were working
on a joint communique that they hoped would reassure nervous
investors that the world's richest countries planned to cooperate
closely on economic matters and currency exchange rates lest signs
of discord further roil financial markets when they open again on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of the final G-7 joint statement expressed optimism that
prospects for the global economy continued to brighten and noted
that Japanese authorities had pledged to keep interest rates low as
long as needed to boost domestic demand, Dow Jones reported.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury statement said Summers and Japanese Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa had agreed to cooperate closely to ensure
''constructive and fruitful'' discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The world's two largest economies have frequently been at odds
in recent years with the United States expressing displeasure at
the widening trade gap between the two nations and Japan's
inability so far to mount a sustained economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Summers and Greenspan held a series of discussions with finance
officials from several countries in Summers' office before the
start of the afternoon G-7 talks, being held at the Blair House,
the government's official guest house across the street from the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa told reporters that Summers told the Japanese
delegation that the plunge in American stock prices had not altered
the strong fundamentals of the U.S. economy, which is currently
enjoying the lowest unemployment rates in three decades and is in
the midst of the longest economic expansion in the country's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is pushing a major package of reforms
of the IMF and World Bank in an effort to head off even more
radical changes being put forward by congressional critics of the
two institutions.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. proposals have drawn objections from other
countries. It was likely the G-7 nations would end up using vague
language pledging support of reforms while leaving the exact
details to be worked out in later meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF on Wednesday issued an economic forecast projecting that
the global economy should grow this year by a healthy 4.2 percent,
the best showing in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the IMF warned that some of the biggest threats to that
forecast resided in the United States, in the form of America's
soaring trade deficit and the potential for a sharp fall in
America's high-flying stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Those worries were dramatically underscored when both the Dow
Jones industrial average and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite
index suffered record point losses on Friday, capping off a dismal
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq is now down 34 percent from its all-time high reached
on March 10, and the Dow Jones industrial average is 10 percent
below its peak reached in January.
</P>
<P>
   The big sell-offs on Friday were triggered by a
worse-than-expected report on inflation which raised fears that the
Federal Reserve, which has already boosted interest rates five
times in an effort to head off price pressures, may be forced to
act much more aggressively, raising the danger of pushing the
country into a recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1641 </TRAILER>
