<HEADLINE> Cuba Boy Poll Shows US Disapproval  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After a week of stalemate, a majority of
Americans disapprove of both the actions of Elian Gonzalez' Miami
family and the Clinton administration, according to a poll released
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Newsweek poll found that 52 percent thought the family was
not cooperating enough with government and court efforts to resolve
the case of the 6-year-old boy. That is up from 41 percent a week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 percent felt the family was cooperating enough in the
efforts to resolve the custody battle of the Cuban shipwreck
survivor, down from 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 752 adults was conducted on Thursday and Friday. It
has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the boy's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez defied the
government's demand that he take the boy to the airport for a
flight to Washington to be reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Disapproval rose, too, for the federal government's efforts to
resolve the case.
</P>
<P>
   A majority -- 53 percent -- disapproved of the way the Clinton
administration and the Justice Department handled the case, up from
49 percent a week earlier. Only 28 percent approved, down from 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unchanged, however, was the majority view that the boy be
reunited with his father in Cuba. Fifty-three percent still
supported that view, while 30 percent said he should remain with
his relatives in Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
