<DOCNO> APW20000415.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FEC filings confirm Giuliani leads Clinton in money game  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's Senate campaign is way
ahead of Hillary Rodham Clinton's in the fund-raising arena, but
huge numbers of small checks are helping both campaigns get rich,
according to Federal Elections Commission filings made public
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's campaign raised $7.36 million between Jan. 1 and
March 31 while Clinton's raised $4.73 million, the campaigns
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns released estimates at the end of March reflecting
similar amounts, but the finalized figures for the quarter were
issued Saturday because of an April 15 deadline from the FEC in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Giuliani raised $12 million and Clinton raised $8
million, bringing the mayor's total to over $19 million and
Clinton's to more than $12. With seven months left before the
election, the Senate race is easily on track to be the most
expensive ever in state history.
</P>
<P>
   These so-called ''hard money'' donations from individual
contributors cannot exceed $2,000 per person. However, both
campaigns are raking in thousands of checks in much smaller
amounts. Clinton received 55,000 donations averaging $82 each for
the quarter, according to her spokesman, Howard Wolfson.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss did not have
figures on individual contributors for the last three-month period,
but she said the $19 million total was comprised of 250,000
contributions overall, which comes out to about an average donation
of about $77.
</P>
<P>
   Glover Weiss did say, however, that 50,000 contributions poured
into the Giuliani campaign during the last two weeks of March.
</P>
<P>
   It was during that period that the mayor faced tremendous local
criticism for his response to the police killing of an unarmed
black man, Patrick Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns have engaged in extensive direct-mail
solicitations. Last year they each raised about half their money
out of state. Neither campaign could say how much money was raised
out of state for the past quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor ended the period with $9.1 million cash on hand while
Clinton had $6.6 million in cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   In expenses, Giuliani's campaign listed $5.6 million for the
three months while Clinton's listed $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Contributor lists bearing the names, addresses and occupations
of every donor will not be available until Monday, the campaigns
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two campaigns will also benefit from additional millions of
dollars in so-called ''soft money'' raised by their respective
parties. There is no cash limit on the amount that political
parties can collect for these unregulated donations. The parties
can then use the money as they see fit to help individual
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign also showed that it has $332,000 in unpaid
bills, while Giuliani's campaign listed $150,000 in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's pending obligations include $60,000 for air travel on
chartered planes.
</P>
<P>
   Glover Weiss reiterated complaints the Giuliani campaign has
made before that Clinton should be reimbursing the government more
for her fund-raising and campaign trips.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been paying for the cost of one first-class airfare
per trip rather than for the actual entire cost of the trip.
Wolfson said that's the standard legal reimbursement formula used
by presidents, vice presidents and first ladies when they campaign
for themselves or others while still in office.
</P>
<P>
   Glover Weiss acknowledged that Clinton is ''following the letter
of the law, but is it right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-15-00 1652 </TRAILER>
