<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World Leaders Seek To Calm Investors
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world's leading financial officials sought to calm
jittery investors by projecting an air of unity today in the face
anti-globalization protesters and one of the worst weeks in Wall Street history.
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
held closed-door talks with America's rich allies to review financial conditions
and ideas to reform the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
Officials said Summers' main message is that the fundamentals of the U.S.
economy remain strong despite a week which saw nearly $2 trillion in wealth
evaporate on Wall Street.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
At Least 40 Dead in Congo Explosion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- A day after a mysterious chain of deadly explosions
struck Kinshasa's international airport, at least 40 people have been reported
dead as Red Cross workers dig through the ruins in a desperate search for
survivors. Reports from Belgium, Congo's former colonial ruler, put the deaths
at between 40 and 50 -- including victims hit by debris up to several miles
away. Hospital officials said 216 were seriously injured. Explanations of what
caused the blasts Friday at Kinshasa's N'Djili international airport ranged from
a short circuit to a soldier's dropping ammunition while unloading a plane full
of weapons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Flag Removal Issue Not Over
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- A proposal that would remove the Confederate flag from
South Carolina's Statehouse dome faces an uphill battle in the state House,
where most black lawmakers say they will vote against the bill. At least 24 of
the 26 black members of the House feel that the bill passed by the Senate on
Thursday doesn't go far enough, said House Minority Leader Gilda Cobb-Hunter.
The bill would take the flag off the dome and out of the House and Senate
chambers, but place a similar flag behind the Confederate Soldier Monument on
the Statehouse grounds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Puts Sequoias Under Protection
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEQUOIA NATIONAL FOREST, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton set aside 328,000
acres of federal forests today to permanently preserve 34 groves of giant
sequoia. In a decision praised by environmentalists but scorned by loggers as a
federal land grab, Clinton ordered the formation of a national monument that
will halt commercial timber sales, mining and some recreational activities.
Clinton already has carved out 2.8 million acres as federal monuments in Utah,
Arizona and California.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Toledo Cites Peru Fraud Attempt
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Setting the tone for his run-off election campaign,
Alejandro Toledo today said last week's massive street protests prevented
President Alberto Fujimori from stealing a third term. ''If the people had not
taken to the streets respectfully, in peace, raising their voices, there would
already be a fraud consummated,'' Toledo told reporters. Fujimori slammed Toledo
for creating an atmosphere of social upheaval that he said could plunge Peru
back into the violence and economic disaster of the 1980s.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Software Glitch at H&AMP;R Block
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- An error in an electronic tax-filing program that
misread intervals of $1,000 as intervals of $1 has left some H&AMP;R Block customers
owing money to the government. H&AMP;R Block has told about 3,000 of its income tax
customers that because of the error, they didn't pay enough money to the
Internal Revenue Service and they will have to send a check, a company spokesman
said today. The problem affects only customers who owed more than $1,000, filed
returns electronically on the company's Tax Cut software or online and had
authorized the IRS to take the payments directly out of their bank accounts.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Denktash Leads Turkish Cypriot Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- With more than half the votes counted, Rauf Denktash
leads the race for president of the self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus today, but is short of the majority necessary to avoid a run-off.
Denktash gathered close to 44 percent of votes, while his main contender, Prime
Minister Dervis Eroglu, has 30 percent, according to the Turkish Cypriot Higher
Election Board. The election for president of the north half of Cyprus -- the
Turkish half -- comes just a month before Turkish Cypriot and Greek Cypriot
leaders will gather in New York to try and find a solution to the island's
division.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees Beat Royals 7-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For 6 1-3 innings, it appeared Ramiro Mendoza would pitch
one of those commonplace perfect games at Yankee Stadium, but Carlos Febles
lined a single off diving third baseman Clay Bellinger's glove with one out in
the seventh, and Mendoza fell short of perfection today in the New York Yankees'
7-1 win over the Royals.
</P>
