<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tons of bizarre trash plucked from N.J. beaches in annual cleanups  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT PLEASANT BEACH, N.J. (AP) -- What do potato chip bags,
bullet casings, tampon applicators, false teeth, gasoline tanks, a
newspaper vending machine and a limbo pole have in common?
</P>
<P>
   All this and more was discarded and found its way onto New
Jersey's beaches. About 3,000 people participated in beach cleanups
Saturday, picking up an amazing array of disgusting detritus.
</P>
<P>
   ''You wouldn't believe the things we find each year,'' said
Cynthia Zipf, executive director of the Clean Ocean Action
environmental group, which sponsors the cleanups each year. ''We've
been doing this for 15 years; hopefully we won't have to keep doing
it for another 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite an incessant drizzle, volunteers fanned out up and down
the coast from the Raritan bayshore to Cape May, picking up and
carrying away anything that didn't belong on the sand or in the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Hook's Gateway National Recreation Area provided a
treasure trove of trash. Among the items recovered there were 4,102
snack food bags such as potato chip wrappers; 421 plastic tampon
applicators, which have earned the derogatory nickname ''New Jersey
beach whistles'' because children pick them up and mistake them for
toys, and a vast array of other plastic items.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers picked up a plastic kiddie pool, a limbo pole, a set
of false teeth, a plastic gasoline container, a light bulb, and a
soggy, blurry traffic ticket issued to a presumably irate motorist,
who then either threw it into the ocean or down a storm drain,
where it made its way to the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Too bad we can't read the name,'' Zipf said. ''Wouldn't that
person love to know the ticket's come back to haunt them?''
</P>
<P>
   Other items collected by volunteers in various locations
included a bowling ball, bullet and shotgun casings, condoms,
underwear (not found near the condoms), a Frisbee, and Zipf's
favorite, a lace doily
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the three discarded fishing nets, numerous
six-pack plastic rings, balloons, bottle caps, aerosol cans, and a
Star-Ledger newspaper vending rack someone tossed onto the sand at
Monmouth Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Still haven't had enough? How 'bout a toilet seat, a bicycle
seat, a rubber mermaid? And to top it all off, one volunteer found
a Polaroid photo of someone's genitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
