<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Leads Race  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- Rauf Denktash failed to capture a
majority of votes in the race for president of the self-declared
Turkish republic in northern Cyprus on Saturday, sending the
elections into a second round of voting.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash is fighting for re-election in the Turkish-run third of
the Mediterranean island a month before new talks with Greek
Cypriots in the south in an attempt to forge a solution to the
island's bitter and protracted division.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash garnered close to 44 percent of votes, while his main
contender, Prime Minister Dervis Eroglu, had 30 percent, according
to the Turkish Cypriot Higher Election Board.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash and Eroglu will face one another in the second round on
April 22, with two left-wing candidates -- Mehmet Ali Talat and
Mustafa Akinci -- acting as power brokers. Talat and Akinci together
took 22 percent of the votes Saturday. Another four percent went to
three other left-wing candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people placed their trust in me again. I will be stronger
to fight for the (Turkish Cypriot) cause on May 23,'' Denktash told
his supporters speaking from the balcony of the presidential
palace, referring to the new talks.
</P>
<P>
   The impending negotiations, the third round of U.N.-mediated
talks to be held in New York, were expected to boost support for
Denktash's campaign as he heads into the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had it been at another time, it wouldn't have been so
important to choose Denktash. But he must finish this peace deal,''
said 25-year-old Gurhum Umut, who said he was voting for the first
time because he was worried that Denktash would need every vote.
</P>
<P>
   But some voters were skeptical that Denktash could achieve peace
after so many years of animosity with Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Denktash hasn't solved the issue in decades. You think he will
now?'' said Mevlut Haci Mevlut, an Eroglu supporter.
</P>
<P>
   After polls closed, a preliminary tally showed that 76 percent
of the electorate voted.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash, 75, established the Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus in 1983 and is leader of his community of 200,000. His
self-declared state is only recognized by Turkey, which maintains
some 30,000 troops on the island.
</P>
<P>
   However, he faced a strong challenge from Eroglu, who has built
support through his role as prime minister and the distribution of
social assistance. Eroglu forced Denktash into a run-off in the
last election in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash had called on voters to cast their ballots for him,
saying ''let's not wait for a second round.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of peace has become more urgent because of the
European Union's membership talks with Cyprus. Turkish Cypriots
want a settlement to be reached soon so the two sides can enter the
EU simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been divided into Turkish and Greek sections since
the 1974 Turkish invasion, which came in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 1711 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
