<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEQUOIA NATIONAL FOREST, Calif. (AP) -- What a difference a light
bulb makes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Saturday he has saved taxpayers big bucks
simply by switching to energy-efficient light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just by changing the lights in the White House, I cut the
power bills $100,000 a year,'' the president said. He said there
were additional savings from installing a new heating system and a
more fuel-efficient roof.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the changes we made in the White House were made in every
federal building ... we would reduce greenhouse gases so much it
would be the equivalent of taking 1.7 million cars a year off the
road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the actual White House savings are larger than Clinton
claimed. A report released last Dec. 2 identified savings of
$300,000 a year including $138,000 from more efficient lighting,
$37,000 from a new heating system and window air conditioner
upgrades and $15,000 from new sprinklers and timers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at a ceremony where he set aside 328,000 acres of
forests to protect giant sequoia trees. He leaned back to gaze up
at soaring sequoia along the Trail of One Hundred Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The president was accompanied on his tour by Eagle scout
Alexander Reed-Krase, who said he has hiked 1,000 miles in Sequoia
National Forest, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and Sequoia
Forest Superintendent Art Gaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chilly day with fresh snow on the ground. Clinton wore
a brown leather bomber jacket with a presidential seal but seemed
surprised by the cold. ''I'm going to have a hard time making the
case for global warming today but I'm going to try, anyway,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish I could stay here all day,'' Clinton said. ''I'd get
warmer pants.'' He marveled that young Reed-Krase wore only a
short-sleeve shirt and wasn't disturbed by the cold. ''I was
thinking that growing older has some merit but one thing it doesn't
have is the ability to withstand cold better,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that the 1990s were the hottest decade on
record, and that Americans must build a consensus to cut down on
emissions of greenhouse gases that many scientists blame for global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   Midway in his speech, Clinton was talking about efforts to
preserve biodiversity. ''The last point I'd like to make is they
won't do much good ... if I get killed by this falling ice.'' That
got everybody's attention. It turned out that a clump of ice had
fallen by his lectern from a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending the afternoon in the forest, Clinton flew to
Palo Alto to play golf at Stanford Golf Course. His foursome
included Geoff Yang, a venture capitalist, Evan Thorney, CEO of
LookSmart.com, and Jack Thyme, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton was heading to Los Angeles for a $2.5 million
fund-raiser with Vice President Al Gore in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
http://www.eren.doe.gov/femp/techassist/green--white--house.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
