<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World Leaders Seek To Calm Investors
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world's leading financial officials, including
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan,
held closed-door talks with America's rich allies today to review financial
conditions in their respective countries. They hoped to calm jittery investors,
comparing ideas on ways to reform the International Monetary Fund and the World
Bank. Officials said Summers' main message is that the fundamentals of the U.S.
economy remain strong despite a week which saw nearly $2 trillion in wealth
evaporate on Wall Street.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rescue Efforts Continue in Congo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Red Cross workers desperately searched for survivors
today, a day after a mysterious chain of explosions at a hangar at Kinshasa's
international airport reportedly killed between 40 and 50 people. Official radio
put the death toll at 10, but reports from Belgium said between 40 and 50 people
had been killed -- including victims hit by debris up to several miles away. The
death toll could rise much higher, with customs officials saying more than 100
people could still be trapped in the hangar. Explanations of what caused the
blasts Friday at Kinshasa's N'Djili international airport ranged from a short
circuit to a soldier's dropping ammunition while unloading a plane full of
weapons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Pray Elian Will Stay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- More than 250 people chanted and prayed outside the Little
Havana home where Elian Gonzalez has been living with his Miami relatives, and
fretted that this weekend might be his last there. In the afternoon, the crowd
began chanting that the boy's father is a coward and a traitor, and that he
should return to Cuba without his son. The 4{-month custody struggle was in the
hands of the federal appeals court in Atlanta, which issued a temporary
injunction Thursday blocking Elian from leaving the country. The Justice
Department also agreed that day to hold off on reuniting Elian with his father
for a few days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Flag Removal Issue Not Over
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- A proposal that would remove the Confederate flag from
South Carolina's Statehouse dome faces an uphill battle in the state House,
where most black lawmakers say they will vote against the bill. At least 24 of
the 26 black members of the House feel that the bill passed by the Senate on
Thursday doesn't go far enough, said House Minority Leader Gilda Cobb-Hunter.
The bill would take the flag off the dome and out of the House and Senate
chambers, but place a similar flag behind the Confederate Soldier Monument on
the Statehouse grounds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Denktash Fails To Capture Majority Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- Rauf Denktash failed to capture a majority of votes
in the race for president of the self-declared Turkish republic in northern
Cyprus on Saturday, sending the elections into a second round of voting.
Denktash is fighting for re-election in the Turkish-run third of the
Mediterranean island a month before new talks with Greek Cypriots in the south
in an attempt to forge a solution to the island's bitter and protracted
division. Denktash and his main rival, Prime Minister Dervis Eroglu, will face
one another in the second round on April 22.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Toledo Cites Peru Fraud Attempt
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Setting the tone for his run-off election campaign,
Alejandro Toledo today said last week's massive street protests prevented
President Alberto Fujimori from stealing a third term. ''If the people had not
taken to the streets respectfully, in peace, raising their voices, there would
already be a fraud consummated,'' Toledo told reporters. Fujimori slammed Toledo
for creating an atmosphere of social upheaval that he said could plunge Peru
back into the violence and economic disaster of the 1980s.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Guatemalan Bus Crash Kills 30
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- An overcrowded bus toppled over in central Guatemala
early Saturday, killing 30 people and injuring at least 50 others. Authorities
were still rescuing people more than seven hours after the crash that happened
just outside Chimaltenango, a city about 60 miles west of Guatemala City. The
driver lost control while taking a curve through the mountainous region in the
state of Sacatepequez. The legal capacity of the bus was 60 passengers, but it
was carrying 100 at the time of the accident.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Wings Defeat Kings 8-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Martin Lapointe scored three times and Kris Draper and Nick
Lidstrom each added two goals as the Detroit Red Wings beat the Los Angeles
Kings 8-5 today, taking a two-game lead in their playoff series. The game was
the highest-scoring playoff game since Los Angeles won 9-6 at Calgary on April
29, 1993.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
