<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Urged on Peace Ideas  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- President Clinton asked Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to bring ideas to the table when they meet in
Washington later this week for discussions on the Mideast peace
process, a Palestinian official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, did not
elaborate on what kind of specific ideas Clinton was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has stepped up its involvement in talks
between Israel and the Palestinians in the face of looming
deadlines -- a peace treaty framework is supposed to concluded next
month, with a full accord by September.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, nearing the end of another
round of talks in Washington, have exchanged documents outlining
their views on a Palestinian state, the future of Jerusalem and
other thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Abed Rabbo, who is leading talks with Israelis at the
Bolling Air Force Base in Washington D.C., said Saturday that the
sides agreed verbally that the framework agreement should address
all the final status issues, which include Jerusalem, Palestinian
refugees, Jewish settlements in the territories and the borders of
a Palestinian entity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Abed Rabbo said there was concern among the
Palestinians that Israel would eventually agree to only a partial
settlement of these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Arafat on Friday to update him on a nearly
four-hour discussion the president had earlier this week with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. Arafat is scheduled to meet with
Clinton at the White House on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader said Israel has procrastinated in talks
on the terms of Palestinian statehood and has systematically
violated agreements while expanding Jewish settlements on lands
claimed by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat thanked the United States for increasing its role as
mediator in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''We demanded that the United States play a role in pushing the
peace process forward, and we thank President Clinton and the U.S.
administration for that role,'' Arafat said Saturday during an
appearance with visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin in
Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat denied an Israel TV report that Barak has offered to
recognize a Palestinian state in 65 percent of the West Bank.
Arafat said no such offer was made.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians insist on an Israeli withdrawal from all the
West Bank, Gaza Strip and east Jerusalem, areas captured by Israel
in the 1967 Mideast war, Arafat said. The Palestinians hope to
build a state on the land.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of several interim agreements, the Palestinians
control about two-thirds of Gaza and 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
