<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Taxpayers Face More Audits  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- It used to be wealthy Americans who had
the most to fear from the Internal Revenue Service. But lately, the
nation's poorest taxpayers have faced a greater likelihood of being
audited, according to a report released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IRS' overall audit rate last year dropped to just
under 1 percent, the focus has shifted from the rich to the poor,
according to Syracuse University's Transactional Records Access
Clearinghouse, which analyzes government data.
</P>
<P>
   Among taxpayers making $100,000 or more, 1.15 percent were
audited in 1999, down from 1.66 a year earlier, TRAC reported. The
rate for those making $25,000 or less was 1.36 percent, up from
1.14 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, IRS auditors have focused on wealthier taxpayers
because they have more to hide from the government and better
opportunities for hiding it. In the early 1990s, taxpayers with
incomes of $100,000 or more were audited at about five times the
rate of those earning less than $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The data is accurate because we provided it to them,'' said
IRS spokesman Don Roberts. ''The interpretations, however, may not
be fully reflective of what additional data might show.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1988, the IRS was clamping down on tax shelter
cheaters so the audit rate for those with incomes over $100,000
jumped to 11.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, the IRS received additional funding to reduce
noncompliance in the earned income tax credit program, or EITC, a
special tax benefit for low-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a reason for more examinations, and it's not because
of their income levels. It is because of items they are claiming on
their returns,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Often, noncompliance in the EITC program involves confusion and
misunderstanding about the eligibility rules rather than deceit and
criminal intent, said Wayne Thomas, the IRS' deputy chief
operations officer.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the same dependent may be claimed by two different
individuals, requiring the IRS to audit both returns to determine
who is entitled to the credit.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the IRS has stepped up its examinations of
nonfilers, he said. Because their incomes are unknown, the
nonfilers are considered part of the lowest income classification.
</P>
<P>
   If the EITC and nonfiler cases are excluded, the audit rate for
low-income Americans is actually 0.17 percent, Thomas said. When
the same is done in the higher income bracket, the rate is 1.08
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''You see the pattern is pretty much what you would expect. The
rate is about seven or eight times greater for the more wealthy,''
Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The revised overall audit rate for the more than 122.5 million
individual returns filed in 1999 would be 0.34 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if this is actually a new, kinder IRS. There are
a lot of dynamics involved here,'' said David Burnham, co-director
for TRAC.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC identified the substantial decline in the size of the IRS
staff as a factor in the changing audit practices. After a buildup
during the Reagan administration, years of budget cuts reduced IRS
staffing from a high of 123,198 employees in 1988 to 97,810 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The more cynical explanation is that the IRS still has enough
significant legal and financial resources left at its disposal that
it is easier to go after a hundred low-income taxpayers that would
just as soon pay the bill than 10 high-income taxpayers with
attorneys,'' said Pete Sepp, a spokesman for the National Taxpayers
Union.
</P>
<P>
   As millions of Americans rush to beat the tax deadline Monday,
they can take consolation in knowing there have been dramatic
declines in the tax agency's three primary enforcement collection
practices: levy, lien and seizure.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking at 3.7 million levies in 1997, IRS agents issued
504,403 levies in 1999 -- an 86 percent drop. Levies are made
against the assets of delinquent taxpayers that are under the
control of a third party, such as bank accounts or wages.
</P>
<P>
   The number of seizures dropped from a yearly average of between
10,000 and 11,000 during the 1990s to only 161 seizures last year,
a 98 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in liens was more gradual. Liens, a legal claim
attached to property, peaked at 1.5 million in 1991 and 1992. By
last year, they dropped to 167,867, a fall of 88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the plunge in levies and seizures was partly the
result of administrative changes required by the IRS Restructuring
and Reform Act of 1998, changes enacted following intense
Congressional criticism of past IRS collection practices.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse:
http://www.trac.syr.edu
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service: http://www.irs.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Taxpayers Union: http://www.ntu.org
</P>
</TEXT>
