<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Backs American's Expulsion  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's Supreme Court rejected an appeal by
a leading American human rights worker who was expelled from Mexico
after visiting the troubled state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled that Mexican authorities acted within
their right in expelling Tom Hansen two years ago, the Interior
Secretariat said in a news release issued Saturday. The ruling was
made on March 17, and there was no explanation for the delay in the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The former director of the Chicago-based Pastors for Peace was
among more than 150 foreigners who were kicked out of the country
for allegedly violating terms of their tourist visas by
participating in political activities in Chiapas, the site of a
5-year-old rebellion by the leftist Zapatista National Liberation
Army.
</P>
<P>
   In September, a senior federal appeals court ruled that
immigration authorities had violated Mexico's constitution by
expelling Hansen and overturned his February 1998 expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   The government promptly rewrote his expulsion order, which was
accepted by a federal judge. Hansen then took his appeal to the
Supreme Court. The court's ruling closes the case for good, the
news release stated.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, who is currently director of the Chicago-based Mexican
Solidarity Network, a coalition of 76 U.S. human rights groups, has
led more than 25 human rights delegations to Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Altamirano, a rebel stronghold, in February 1998 to
distribute video equipment to Tzeltal Indians as part of the
U.S.-Mexico Fund for Culture project, which was financed by the
Rockefeller Foundation and the Mexican government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
