<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Make Mass Arrests in D.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Anti-globalization protesters swarmed through the heart of
the capital late today and came face to face with lines of helmeted police in a
tense show of will sparked by animosity toward international lending
institutions. Several hundred were arrested for parading without a permit and
led peacefully away to at least seven yellow school buses as supporters shouted
for police to let them go. Police pulled the fake red nose off one protester
dressed as a clown as he filed into the bus. In downtown Washington, riot-ready
police made some 50 blocks off limits around the World Bank headquarters,
barring everyone from getting past metal barriers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Zimbabwe Squatters Kill White Farmer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Squatters occupying white-owned land shot to death a
farmer and abducted four others, farmers leaders said Sunday, a killing that
could deepen the crisis over Zimbabwe's tense land standoff. David Stevens was
abducted from his occupied property near Macheke, 75 miles east of Harare and
driven into the bush where he was shot dead, said Commercial Farmers Union
officials. Four of Stevens' neighbors who went to his assistance after he was
confronted by squatters Saturday were abducted and their whereabouts were not
immediately known, the union said. Another neighbor, John Osborne, who witnessed
the killing, said Stevens -- in his 40s -- was hit in the head and back by
shotgun blasts, the union said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rescue Efforts Continue in Congo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Red Cross workers desperately searched for survivors
today, a day after a mysterious chain of explosions at a hangar at Kinshasa's
international airport reportedly killed between 40 and 50 people. Official radio
put the death toll at 10, but reports from Belgium said between 40 and 50 people
had been killed -- including victims hit by debris up to several miles away. The
death toll could rise much higher, with customs officials saying more than 100
people could still be trapped in the hangar. Explanations of what caused the
blasts Friday at Kinshasa's N'Djili international airport ranged from a short
circuit to a soldier's dropping ammunition while unloading a plane full of
weapons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poor Taxpayers Face More Audits
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- According to a report released today, the nation's
poorest taxpayers face a greater likelihood of being audited. Though the IRS'
overall audit rate last year dropped to just under 1 percent, the focus has
shifted from the rich to the poor, according to Syracuse University's
Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse, which analyzes government data.
Among taxpayers making $100,000 or more, 1.15 percent were audited in 1999, down
from 1.66 a year earlier, TRAC reported. The rate for those making $25,000 or
less was 1.36 percent, up from 1.14 in 1998.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Whaling Trade Plans Rejected
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- In a major setback Saturday, Japan and Norway lost
bids to win international approval for limited trade of the grey and minke
whales. In a secret ballot, 53 countries attending the U.N. conference on trade
in endangered species voted against a proposal that would have allowed
controlled trade of the whale. Forty countries voted in favor of the plan and
nine abstained. Delegates also rejected two other Japanese proposals to allow
controlled trade in minke whales located in the southern hemisphere and in an
area from the Okhotsak Sea to the western Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Pray Elian Will Stay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- More than 250 people chanted and prayed outside the Little
Havana home where Elian Gonzalez has been living with his Miami relatives, and
fretted that this weekend might be his last there. In the afternoon, the crowd
began chanting that the boy's father is a coward and a traitor, and that he
should return to Cuba without his son. The 4{-month custody struggle was in the
hands of the federal appeals court in Atlanta, which issued a temporary
injunction Thursday blocking Elian from leaving the country. The Justice
Department also agreed that day to hold off on reuniting Elian with his father
for a few days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lightbulbs Changed at White House
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEQUOIA NATIONAL FOREST, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton said today he has
saved taxpayers big bucks simply by switching to energy-efficient light bulbs.
He said there were additional savings from installing a new heating system and a
more fuel-efficient roof. A report released last Dec. 2 identified savings of
$300,000 a year including $138,000 from more efficient lighting, $37,000 from a
new heating system and window air conditioner upgrades and $15,000 from new
sprinklers and timers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sharks Beat Blues 4-2, Series Tied
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mike Ricci scored a power-play goal with 5:42 left to lead
eighth-seeded San Jose Sharks to a 4-2 victory today over the St. Louis Blues.
The best-of-7 series is tied 1-1 and heads to San Jose for Game 3 on Monday
night.
</P>
