<DOCNO> APW20000415.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fusaichi Pegasus Wins at Aqueduct  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD ROSENBLATT, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In the final 220 yards of the $750,000 Wood
Memorial, Fusaichi Pegasus showed why he is sure to be the
unquestioned favorite for the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Unleashing a powerful finishing kick, Fusaichi Pegasus cruised
past Red Bullet and Country Only for an easy 4\-length victory in
the 1[-mile Wood at Aqueduct on a rainy Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He justified himself as the Kentucky Derby favorite,'' trainer
Neil Drysdale said. ''I could not have asked for a better
performance. Just look at him coming back -- he adores looking
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong-willed Fusaichi Pegasus has a habit of checking out
the surroundings before and after a race. So much so that Drysdale
says he has a ''mind of his own, and when he decides to do it, he
does it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did it on the East Coast for the first time, where he
obviously found a new racing surface, a wet track and a large field
of 12 3-year-olds to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet, beaten for the first time in four starts, held on
for second, with Aptitude third and Country Only fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In adding the Wood to his previous win in the San Felipe Stakes
on March 19 at Santa Anita, Fusaichi Pegasus has now beaten many of
the other top Derby contenders. He defeated The Deputy in the San
Felipe, a colt who went on to win the Santa Anita Derby on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a major, major step,'' Fusaichi Pegusas' jockey Kent
Desormeaux said. ''This horse showed me the capability of being
able to sprint to a spot, go on cruise control, sprint to a spot
later on, go back on cruise control and then really stretch out
when you ask him for his life late in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus lived up to his pedigree and price tag against
one of the strongest fields in 76 runnings of the Wood.
</P>
<P>
   He is a son of the late Mr. Prospector, out of a Danzig dam,
Angel Fever, and was purchased for an eye-popping $4 million at the
1998 Keeneland July Sale by Japanese entrepreneur Fusao Sekiguchi,
who said he would have paid $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus looked like he was worth every penny Sekiguchi
paid as he cruised behind the leaders, then made his move around
the final turn. Country Only, ridden by Herbert Castillo Jr., was
the pace-setter, with Red Bullet right behind.
</P>
<P>
   The two stayed that way until they entered the stretch. And
that's when Desormeaux asked Fusaichi Pegasus to run a little
faster.
</P>
<P>
   ''I gave him some underhand slashes under the girth, but that
was just to keep his attention,'' Desormeaux said. ''I nibbled on
him a little, and he took right off. I wanted him to keep reaching
late and to keep reaching until after we said, 'OK, big fella,
you've done enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus covered the 1[ miles in 1:47 4-5 over track
labeled good. The strapping colt was the 4-5 favorite of the crowd
of 15,684, and returned $3.80, $2.70 and $2.20. Red Bullet, ridden
by Alex Solis, paid $3.60 and $2.80 and Aptitude, trained by Hall
of Fame trainer Bobby Frankel, got up for third and paid $3.20.
</P>
<P>
   After Country Only, Appearing Now was fifth, followed by
Postponed, Cat's at Home, Painted Pistol, Exchange Rate, Fight for
Ally, Connect and Traditionally.
</P>
<P>
   In the two other major prep races, the D. Wayne Lukas-trained
High Yield won the Blue Grass Stakes at Keeneland and Graeme Hall
won the Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn Park.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Orseno, who trains Derby-bound Red Bullet, said his colt was
a little too close to the lead but, ''if Alex had taken him back he
most probably would have gotten into traffic trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''Will he move up from this race? I think he will but the
question is how much because the winner ran a very big race.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the race, Fusaichi Pegasus took longer than most to get
to the start before he was finally led into his No. 5 gate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope he wants to come out and play today,'' Desormeaux
remembered thinking.
</P>
<P>
   After he won, Desormeaux had a tough time getting Fusaichi
Pegasus back to the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   But when he did, he smiled at Sekiguchi's daughter, Yukari, and
said, ''he's a rebel with a cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus earned $450,000 for the win and can earn a
$250,000 bonus if he completes the Wood-Derby double.
</P>
<P>
   The last Wood winner to take the Kentucky Derby was Pleasant
Colony in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, Precise End won the $110,000 Bay Shore by 5\
lengths over Turnofthecentury; Brutally Frank won by a head over
Kelly Kip in the $100,000 Bold Ruler; and '99 Belmont Stakes and
Travers winner Lemon Drop Kid and End of the Road finished in a
dead heat in a $60,000 allowance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
