<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analyses of NFL Draft Picks  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY WILNER, AP Football Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A look at how each NFL team addressed its needs
in Saturday's NFL draft:
</P>
<P>
CLEVELAND
</P>
<P>
   The second-year Browns need plenty and could have gotten several
extra selections by trading down. Instead, they stuck to their plan
of taking an impact player, COURTNEY BROWN, DE, PENN STATE. He
should start immediately and be visiting the Pro Bowl in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   A division champion rarely picks so high. The Skins, through
deals with New Orleans and San Francisco, moved into position to
put a stranglehold on the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   LAVAR ARRINGTON, LB, PENN STATE, has been compared in some
quarters to Lawrence Taylor. While that might be unfair, he should
be a factor right away, helping plug up a porous defense.
</P>
<P>
   The other choice, CHRIS SAMUELS, OT, Alabama, fills perhaps a
bigger need at left tackle, protecting Brad Johnson and opening
running room for Stephen Davis.
</P>
<P>
CINCINNATI
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye Carl Pickens? The Bengals are looking to dump their
disgruntled wideout, and have the perfect replacement now in
game-breaking PETER WARRICK, WR, FLORIDA STATE. Warrick also should
star immediately on special teams and gives Akili Smith another
deep threat to go with Darnay Scott.
</P>
<P>
BALTIMORE
</P>
<P>
   Offense-minded coach Brian Billick was seeking a running back
and a wideout from the first round. The runner became JAMAL LEWIS,
Tennessee, who has been injury prone, but has size and speed. He's
considered a better inside runner than Thomas Jones, the other top
RB in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver came 10th overall as Baltimore grabbed TRAVIS
TAYLOR, FLORIDA. Although injured for much of last season, Taylor
is a speedy deep threat with good hands. The Ravens got just what
they wanted.
</P>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles could be putting together a decent front four if Hugh
Douglas and Mike Mamula can stay healthy to join COREY SIMON, DT,
FLORIDA STATE. Simon was, by far, the best player at his position
and fills an immediate void, even if a receiver might have seemed a
bigger need.
</P>
<P>
ARIZONA
</P>
<P>
   With THOMAS JONES, RB, VIRGINIA, the Cardinals got a very
necessary tool for a lagging offense. They haven't had a real
threat at running back in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
PITTSBURGH
</P>
<P>
   If coach Bill Cowher's job is on the line this season, he at
least got a potential playmaker to help him keep it in PLAXICO
BURRESS, WR, MICHIGAN STATE. Considered something of an attitude
problem, Burress' skills and size (6-5) make him an attractive
target if Kordell Stewart can find him.
</P>
<P>
CHICAGO
</P>
<P>
   A new Monster of the Midway in versatile BRIAN URLACHER, LB, NEW
MEXICO. Urlacher also can play safety or tight end, but at 6-4, 258
with speed, he will go at outside linebacker. Not the biggest need
for Chicago, but he's too good an athlete to pass up, and the Bears
felt they could get a receiver, cornerback or running back later
on.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK GIANTS
</P>
<P>
   Wanted a heavy-duty running back. Got a heavy-duty running back
in Heisman Trophy winner RON DAYNE, WISCONSIN. While he'll have to
do a lot of work on his own behind a weak offensive line, Dayne can
move piles better than some of the Giants' blockers. And he's
almost as big.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK JETS
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trade their way up -- or down -- the Jets used their
four first-rounders. In consecutive picks, they aided the defense
with SHAUN ELLIS, DE, TENNESSEE, and JOHN ABRAHAM, LB, SOUTH
CAROLINA. Ellis could be the pass rusher they desperately need, but
Abraham does not fill a need, unless the team is planning to trade
Mo Lewis or Roman Phifer.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lucas' development at quarterback apparently didn't impress
new coach Al Groh enough, because the Jets went for CHAD
PENNINGTON, MARSHALL, at No. 18. Pennington will be groomed as
Vinny Testaverde's eventual replacement, although Lucas would like
a say in that.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing off their unprecedented mother lode in the opening
round, the Jets addressed a major problem with ANTHONY BECHT, TE,
WEST VIRGINIA. He will need to improve his blocking, but has little
competition at the position.
</P>
<P>
GREEN BAY
</P>
<P>
   The Packers breathed a whole lot easier when BUBBA FRANKS, TE,
MIAMI (FLA.), was not taken by the Jets. Franks can be a playmaker
at the position, and with Mark Chmura facing an uncertain future,
this was a wise choice.
</P>
<P>
DENVER
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos really must be worried about Dale Carter's pending
suspension. Why else go for DELTHA O'NEAL, CB, CALIFORNIA, who was
projected as a second-rounder, with the 15th pick? O'Neal will help
as a kick returner.
</P>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO
</P>
<P>
   Wanted: a pass-rushing linebacker. Acquired: a pass-rushing
linebacker, JULIAN PETERSON, MICHIGAN STATE. He should fill two
needs if he upgrades his pass coverage, and immediately adds
athletic ability to a lagging defense.
</P>
<P>
   More Big Ten help for the defense came in the 24th spot when the
Niners selected AHMED PLUMMER, CB, OHIO STATE. He should start
immediately and gives San Francisco some size, which it lacked on
the corner.
</P>
<P>
OAKLAND
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Rebel placekicker SEBASTIAN JANIKOWSKI, FLORIDA STATE,
who has been accused of trying to bribe a policeman, could wind up
being deported to his native Poland. He has a bigtime leg,
regularly hitting from beyond 50 yards, and he sends nearly every
kickoff into the end zone. But a kicker at No. 17 overall when
wideout and defensive end were more critical areas is a reach.
</P>
<P>
SEATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Watters is slowing down, and the Seahawks stole a player
the next two teams in line wanted by choosing SHAUN ALEXANDER, RB,
ALABAMA. But needing an inside linebacker, deep receiving threat
and a blocker, why make this move? Maybe Watters is on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   And three spots later, the Seahawks chose someone to open holes
for Alexander in CHRIS MCINTOSH, OT, WISCONSIN. Mike Holmgren looks
like he's serious about upgrading the running game.
</P>
<P>
DETROIT
</P>
<P>
   The Lions went into the draft looking to add a guard who could
play on the left side between Ray Roberts and Mike Compton, and
seem to have gotten their man in STOCKAR McDOUGLE, OT, OKLAHOMA.
McDougle is a superior run blocker who rarely commits penalties.
</P>
<P>
KANSAS CITY
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs would have loved Dayne or Alexander. At least they
helped their mediocre receiving corps with SYLVESTER MORRIS, WR,
JACKSON STATE, who can get deep, but is a bit of a project. The
running game still needs addressing.
</P>
<P>
CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   With a pair of aging cornerbacks in Doug Evans and Eric Davis,
both of whom have seen their best days, the Panthers opted for
RASHARD ANDERSON, JACKSON STATE. The top three offensive linemen
were gone, so the Panthers went after another weak spot, but they
must wish McIntosh or McDougle had fallen to them.
</P>
<P>
MINNESOTA
</P>
<P>
   Although the offensive line and secondary are lacking, the
Vikings went for help for John Randle on the defensive line with
CHRIS HOVAN, DT, BOSTON COLLEGE. A bit one-dimensional, he should
occupy blockers to free Randle more.
</P>
<P>
BUFFALO
</P>
<P>
   You lose Bruce Smith, you go for a defensive end who can get
into the opposing backfield. ERIK FLOWERS, ARIZONA STATE, fits the
bill and figures to start.
</P>
<P>
INDIANAPOLIS
</P>
<P>
   Thinning at linebacker, the Colts went for ROB MORRIS, BYU, who
will be placed on the inside, where he shouldn't have any trouble
becoming a starter. Indianapolis' offense is high tech and the
defense needs to become more stingy. This should help.
</P>
<P>
JACKSONVILLE
</P>
<P>
   Needing speed at receiver, the Jaguars ignored a gaping hole at
guard to select unpredictable R. JAY SOWARD, SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA.
If Mark Brunell gets enough time, he'll have another threat on the
outside to join Jimmy Smith and Keenan McCardle.
</P>
<P>
TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   Not overwhelming at linebacker, the Titans went for a
run-stuffer who should do well in coverage in KEITH BULLUCK,
SYRACUSE. They needed a defensive tackle more, but didn't see one
to their liking, and there were no tight end prospects in sight.
</P>
<P>
ST. LOUIS
</P>
<P>
   A strange pick to finish off the first round. One thing the Rams
have plenty of is game-breaking types on offense. They need
offensive linemen. Yet they went for TRUNG CANIDATE, RB, ARIZONA,
who was looked at as a mid-second-round guy. Then again, they won
the Super Bowl, so cut them some slack.
</P>
<P>
NEW ORLEANS
</P>
<P>
   After trading what would have been the No. 2 overall pick in the
Ricky Williams deal last year, the Saints had to wait until No. 33.
They need a strong fullback to block for Williams and depth in the
secondary, but opted instead for DARREN HOWARD, DE, KANSAS STATE,
an impressive pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons addressed a number of needs with free-agent
signings, but still had a few holes to fill. One was on offensive
line, where TRAVIS CLARIDGE, OT, SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA, expected by
some to be a first-rounder, can play right tackle or guard.
</P>
<P>
SAN DIEGO
</P>
<P>
   After signing free agent wide receiver Curtis Conway, the
Chargers went into the draft focused on adding a linebacker or
depth in the secondary. They went for ROGERS BECKETT, S, MARSHALL,
who is a hard hitter in the Tim McDonald mold.
</P>
<P>
NEW ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots desperately need a running back, but went for
ADRIAN KLEMM, OT, HAWAII, in the second round. Klemm, projected by
some as a first-rounder, could develop into a solid left tackle.
Now, New England needs someone to run behind him.
</P>
<P>
DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   With the likely loss of Deion Sanders, the Cowboys were in need
of a defensive back. DWAYNE GOODRICH, DB, TENNESSEE, has
outstanding speed and is superb in man-to-man coverage. Still,
Goodrich will be hard-pressed to step into Sanders' shoes.
</P>
<P>
TAMPA BAY
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers' primary need was at wide receiver -- until they
pulled off a trade with the New York Jets to get Keyshawn Johnson.
So, Tampa Bay focused on upgrading the offensive line. It traded up
six spots to ensure it would get CASEY COLEMAN, G, TENNESSEE,
regarded by many as the best all-around lineman available.
</P>
<P>
MIAMI
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins probably won't re-sign Pro Bowler Richmond Webb
after next season, so TODD WADE, OT, MISSISSIPPI, is the
replacement-in-waiting. Like several offensive linemen taken in the
second round, Wade was considered a possible first-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
