<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressHenry Walker
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- Henry A. Walker Jr., who turned a sugar company
laden with debts into one with assets worth billions, died of
leukemia Friday. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was named president of Amfac Inc. in 1967 and chairman
and chief executive officer in 1973, a position he held until he
retired in 1983. He became chairman again in 1987 after a company
restructuring and was named chairman emeritus the following year
after Amfac was acquired by Chicago-based JMB Realty Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, Amfac became the first Hawaii company, in
1974, to reach $1 billion in annual revenues. The company later
reached annual revenues of $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's father, H. Alexander Walker Sr., joined the company in
1927 when it was known as American Factors Ltd. He became president
of the company in 1927. The elder Walker died in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   His son joined the company in 1947 as a truck driver's helper,
and worked his way through the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawaii-born Walker served in the Navy and was aboard the
battleship USS Missouri during the World War II surrender ceremony
in Tokyo Bay on Sept. 2, 1945. He played a key role in bringing the
Missouri to Hawaii in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-15-00 2153 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
