<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer victim's dream of pro ball players realized before death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP)-- Eleven-year-old Jimmy Schneeberger lost his
long bout with cancer Thursday, but not without realizing his
dream.
</P>
<P>
   With a tumor at the base of his brain stem that was first
diagnosed by doctors in 1997, the Naples, Fla. boy had little
choice but to undergo extensive and painful therapies. They
included a full regimen of radiation and chemotherapy, a bone
marrow and stem cell transplant, and three surgeries in two years --
only to have the tumor grow back.
</P>
<P>
   In December, The Wishing Well Foundation of Marco Island, Fla.,
arranged for Schneeberger to meet Dominik Hasek, Michael Peca,
Brian Holzinger and Rob Ray at a Sabres practice. As guests of the
hockey team, the Schneebergers watched the Sabres end a five-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Also that weekend, the young sports fan had the opportunity to
toss a football and shoot the breeze with Doug Flutie in the Bill's
field house before attending a Sunday game with his parents and
siblings as guests of the Bills. Players from the football team
presented Schneeberger with autographed jerseys and footballs to
show off to his friends at home in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His parents said they are grateful for what their son
experienced from Buffalo athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ''He probably had the dream week of any little boy,'' Jim
Schneeberger said. ''It was a great, great visit, and there were a
lot of big moments for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a dream vacation on many levels, but Jimmy's
parents received some bad news from doctors at Children's Hospital
and Roswell Park Cancer Institute during their stay.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cancer had spread to his spine,'' said Jim Schneeberger.
</P>
<P>
   Experimental therapy at Texas Children's Hospital in Houston
didn't work. After a five-week stay there, Jimmy came home for a
visit but never went back.
</P>
<P>
   ''He died at home with his mother holding one hand and his
father holding the other,'' Jim Schneeberger told the Buffalo News.
''We were both right there when he gave his final breath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
