<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expos-Phillies Game Rained Out  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rain kept the Philadelphia Phillies from
playing, but a game in Florida had many people in the organization
watching.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies and Expos were rained out Saturday night before
they could get underway. Philadelphia ace Curt Schilling,
recovering from offseason shoulder surgery, made a start for
Single-A Clearwater.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling was impressive in his third rehab start, throwing 79
pitches in five shutout innings. He allowed one hit and one walk
and struck out seven.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has been nothing but encouraging,'' Phillies manager Terry
Francona said. ''Except for a few days in February, he has been
phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling's pitches topped out at 94 mph and averaged between 91
and 92 mph, but Francona refused to discuss when he would rejoin
the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ''He needs to complete spring training,'' Francona said. ''We
need to be careful how we treat Schilling. When he's ready believe
me we'll pitch him. His arm will dictate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies were debating whether to move Schilling to Triple-A
Scranton-Wilkes-Barre or leave him in Clearwater for his next rehab
start.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want him to pitch, that is the important thing,'' Francona
said, ''Everyone would like him to pitch to better competition but
we don't want him to miss a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling has a timetable that he is shooting for.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did some things tonight that made me feel good,'' he said.
''If all goes well, I'm definitely going to pitch on the 20th in
Clearwater and then on the 25th in Scranton.''
</P>
<P>
   He could return to the Phillies and make a start at home on
April 30 against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   '' That is the date I had planned on for three months,''
Schilling said.
</P>
<P>
   No makeup date has been announced for the rainout, which was
announced after a delay of 1 hour, 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will keep their pitching rotations the same with
Philadelphia's Andy Ashby going against Montreal's Hideki Irabu on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a shame we couldn't get the game in,'' Montreal manager
Felipe Alou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
