<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
600 World Bank Protesters Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 600 anti-globalization protesters, swarming through
the capital Saturday to show animosity toward international lending
institutions, were arrested. Police Chief Charles Ramsey said they would be
charged with ''parading without a permit and refusal to disperse, among other
things.'' Some might also be charged with blocking traffic, he added. Riot-ready
police made some 50 blocks off-limits around the World Bank headquarters,
barring everyone from getting past metal barriers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Dad Denies Abuse Claims
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Demonstrators in Little Havana called Elian Gonzalez's father a
traitor and a coward on Saturday while Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in an interview
with CBS to be aired Sunday, denied accusations he was abusive and said he was
being falsely characterized. The protesters' chants came a day after affidavits
filed by the boy's Miami relatives alleged the father abused his ex-wife and
6-year-old son. The 4{-month custody struggle was in the hands of the federal
appeals court in Atlanta, which issued a temporary injunction Thursday blocking
Elian from leaving the country. The Justice Department also agreed that day to
hold off on reuniting Elian with his father for a few days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Zimbabwe Farmer Said Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- A farmer was shot and killed and four others were
abducted Saturday by squatters occupying white-owned land, farmers said Sunday,
a killing that could deepen the crisis over Zimbabwe's tense land standoff.
David Stevens was abducted from his occupied property near Macheke, 75 miles
east of Harare, and driven into the bush where he was shot dead, said Commercial
Farmers Union officials. Four of Stevens' neighbors who went to his assistance
after he was confronted by squatters Saturday were abducted and their
whereabouts were not immediately known, the union said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congo Blast Rescue Mission Continues
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Red Cross workers desperately searched for survivors
Saturday, a day after a mysterious chain of explosions at a hangar at Kinshasa's
international airport reportedly killed between 40 and 50 people. Official radio
put the death toll at 10, but reports from Belgium said between 40 and 50 people
had been killed -- including victims hit by debris up to several miles away. The
death toll could rise much higher, with customs officials saying more than 100
people could still be trapped in the hangar. Explanations of what caused the
blasts Friday at Kinshasa's N'Djili international airport ranged from a short
circuit to a soldier's dropping ammunition while unloading a plane full of
weapons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Gore Appear Together in LA
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore touted Internet access as an antidote to
inner-city woes today before collecting millions of dollars for Democrats at a
star-studded Beverly Hills dinner with President Clinton -- their first joint
appearance in more than four months. The vice president attended the opening of
the first ''cyber cafe'' in the South-Central Los Angeles area, praising it as a
step in closing the so-called digital divide. Gore was introduced as ''an
honorary black man'' to the crowd, made up mostly of minorities.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Student Wins $10M on Web Sweepstakes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A San Jose college student won $10 million Saturday in an
Internet company promotion, and said he will use some of the money to buy his
parents a house. ''I'm so in shock right now. I'm speechless,'' Lee Truong, 24,
said by telephone from a studio at CBS. Truong was selected randomly from four
finalists in the ''iWon.com Annual $10 Million Giveaway'' special, which CBS
televised live two days before Tax Day (The IRS gets nearly $3.5 million of the
prize). Truong said he planned to buy a house for his parents, who run a family
restaurant.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Orioles' Ripken Gets 3,000th Hit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Cal Ripken got his 3,000th hit Saturday, adding another
huge number to his Hall of Fame resume. The Baltimore Orioles star, already
renowned for playing a record 2,632 straight games, reached this milestone with
his third hit of the game. Ripken became the 24th player to reach 3,000 hits,
doing it a year after both Tony Gwynn and Wade Boggs joined the club. Ripken
lined a clean single to center field off reliever Hector Carrasco for No. 3,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cavaliers Defeat Knicks 106-96
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- The New York Knicks' chances of winning the Atlantic
Division took a huge hit Saturday night as they lost decisively on the road for
the second night in a row, 106-96 to the Cleveland Cavaliers. Andre Miller
scored 18 points to lead six Cleveland players in double figures. New York
(49-31), coming off a 15-point loss at Toronto, fell 1{ games behind Miami.
AP NewsBrief By RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
